# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charles-william-eliot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The **20th Century Press Archives** (German: *Pressearchiv 20.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert*) comprises about 19 million newspaper clippings, organized in folders about persons, companies, wares, events and topics.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] It originates from the Hamburg Kolonialinstitut (colonial institute) founded in 1908.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Within the Hamburg Institute of International Economics (HWWA) it turned into a unique public press archive.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 2007 it was absorbed by the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) and merged with the Wirtschaftsarchiv (economics archive) of the Kiel Institute for the World Economy (IfW), founded in 1914.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Article collection was discontinued at the end of 2005, but the archive is still open to the public.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The archive has its origins in two institutions in the German cities of Hamburg and Kiel.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In Hamburg, after a few years, the "Zentralstelle" (central office) of the Kolonialinstitut was transformed from a free information center for colonial issues into a comprehensive archive of global political and economic topics, which primarily supported the city's merchants.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] After the breakdown of the German colonial empire in World War I, the renaming to "Hamburgisches Welt-Wirtschafts-Archiv" in 1919 sealed this reorientation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The staff of HWWA reflected its importance and grew from 54 in 1919 to 183 permanent or temporary employees in 1958 – a number that seems to have remained largely stable until the late 1990s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Founded shortly before the outbreak of the First World War, the Kiel Economic Archive and its library were closely linked to the scientific work of the IfW, which focused on global economic contexts and their practical use.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 1966, the library of the IfW was given the function of a central library for economics by the German Research Foundation (DFG) in the Federal Republic of Germany, and in 1993, the department was renamed accordingly.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] During the first and second world wars, both archives were intensively involved in the foreign and wartime planning of the empire and the Nazi state.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Starting in 1936, "Confidential Reports from the Foreign Press" provided selected economic leaders and Nazi departments with "largely unfiltered information and comments on economic issues from foreign media and represented a unique feature in Nazi media policy".
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Acting with the informal means of a foreign cultural and information policy supplementing the military expansion policy, HWWA and IfW dedicated their services to the Nazi regime.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 1996, a closer cooperation between HWWA and ZBW / Wirtschaftsarchiv began, with the aim of merging the two archives.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] From the beginning of 2001, the articles were indexed according to a new common classification system and made retrievable via a reference database, "EconPress".
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Following a recommendation from an evaluation within the Leibniz Association in 2003, the current press documentation was finished at the end of 2005 and the materials were frozen at that point.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The separate existence of the HWWA ended in 2007 with the integration of its press documentation and library into the ZBW as a newly formed foundation under public law.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Today, the press archive belongs to the (research) organisations of the Leibniz Association.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] By 1919 at the latest, the Hamburg archive collected "press clippings on a global scale".
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] More than 1400 sources were monitored for the press archives.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Their broad international distribution provides access to the history of political thought and receptive history of the covered topics.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Occasionally, the collected publications go back as far as 1826.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] While the persons archive was only available in paper form until its partial digitization, the holdings of the topics, wares and companies archives were saved every ten years on roll film or microfiche since the 1960s and then the paper clippings were pulped.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The holdings of the Kiel Wirtschaftsarchiv are less comprehensively documented.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The "war archive" of 1914–1918, which amounted to one million clippings, was destroyed by a bomb strike in 1942.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 1958, when six scientific experts and more than 30 employees in total were collecting and organizing the material, the total extent of the archive was estimated as more than three million, and in 1993 as more than ten million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert* application, parts of the holdings of both archives are now accessible on the web.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] From 2004 to 2007, the German Research Foundation funded a project to digitize parts of the archives, namely the materials from the beginning up to 1949 (the formation of the Federal Republic of Germany).
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The paper clippings from the folders of the persons archive were scanned, and metadata (folder and document ID as well as page number, occasionally also source, publication date, author and title) were recorded by project staff.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Optical character recognition could not be applied due to the partially used Fraktur scripts, the constantly changing fonts (as well as languages) in the sequence of the articles, and the sometimes poor quality of the clippings.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] However, the approximately 5,500 person folders created before 1949 are fully accessible online.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The roll film parts of the archive (up to 1960) have also been digitized.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] As neither the folders nor the documents on these films were separated in a machine-readable fashion, such formal elements could not be automatically derived.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Instead, the pages had to be "sliced" with specially developed "Slider" software, assembled into documents and folders, and given metadata.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Only a small part of this labor-intensive process was finished at the end of the project in 2007.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] It is continued today, so that new folders are continually made available via the web application "Pressemappe 20.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Jahrhundert", which was created within the framework of the project.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] 11,000 company folders on digitized roll film, by 2018 about 7,500 were accessible online.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] For the topics and wares archives, the proportion of online folders seems to be significantly lower.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The persons are alphabetically indexed by name, while the companies are accessible by name, geographically by their headquarters and via industry lists.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The topics can be accessed via the topics hierarchy and country system as well as through a search for subject and geographical GND keywords, and via a world map with geolocations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] The limitation to 1949 was made for capacity reasons, and due to intellectual property rights restrictions.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] Numerous individual articles within the dossiers are subject to blocking notices if the death of the author (or in the case of anonymous or pseudonymous works, the date of publication) is less than 70 years ago.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] With a moving wall more and more documents should be released over time.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] How many of the about 5.7 million documents digitized in the context of the project are accessible to the scientific and general public on the web is not known.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 2019, the German National Library of Economics (ZBW) placed all the metadata of the archives under a CC0 licence, and began a cooperation and "data donation" with Wikimedia Deutschland.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] This led to the creation of many new Wikidata items and the enrichment of many existing items; by the end of 2022, every folder in the archive was connected to items in Wikidata.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] In 2024, changes to intellectual property rights in Europe made it possible to provide complete digitized images from the archive – some 3.8 million pages – for online viewing within the European Union.
[src:charles-william-eliot/20th-century-press-archives] A volunteer project is working on adding links to the archive's folders in Wikidata, so that Wikidata provides an index to the material.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] The following is a partial list of minor planets, running from minor-planet number 5001 through 6000, inclusive.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] The primary data for this and other partial lists is based on JPL's "Small-Body Orbital Elements" and data available from the Minor Planet Center.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] Critical list information is also provided by the MPC, unless otherwise specified from Lowell Observatory.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] A detailed description of the table's columns and additional sources are given on the main page including a complete list of every page in this series, and a statistical break-up on the dynamical classification of minor planets.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] Also see the summary list of all named bodies in numerical and alphabetical order, and the corresponding naming citations for the number range of this particular list.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] New namings may only be added to this list after official publication, as the preannouncement of names is condemned by the Working Group for Small Bodies Nomenclature of the International Astronomical Union.
[src:charles-william-eliot/5202-1983-xx-p01] J. van Houten, I. van Houten-Groeneveld, T.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] With an "aristocratic sense of mission and self-certainty," Lowell initiated significant reforms at Harvard.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His years as president saw an expansion of the university in terms of the size of its physical infrastructure, its student body, and its endowment.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His reform of undergraduate education established the system of majoring in a particular discipline that became the standard in American education.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He demonstrated outspoken support for academic freedom during World War I and played a prominent role in urging the public to support American participation in the League of Nations following the war.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Yet his Harvard years saw two public disputes in which he argued for compromising basic principles of justice for the sake of his own personal vision of Harvard's mission with respect to assimilating non-traditional students.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In one instance, he tried to limit Jewish enrollment to 15% of the student body.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In the other, he tried to ban African-American students from living in the Freshman Halls when all of Harvard's new students were required to room there.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In both cases the Harvard Board of Overseers insisted on the consistent application of liberal principles and overruled him.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell was born on December 13, 1856, in Boston, Massachusetts, the second son of Augustus Lowell and Katherine Bigelow Lowell.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His mother was a cousin of architect Charles H.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] A member of the Brahmin Lowell family, his siblings included the poet Amy Lowell, the astronomer Percival Lowell, and Elizabeth Lowell Putnam, an early activist for prenatal care.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] They were the great-grandchildren of John Lowell and, on their mother's side, the grandchildren of Abbott Lawrence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell graduated from Noble and Greenough School in 1873 and attended Harvard College where he presented a thesis for honors in mathematics that addressed using quaternions to treat quadrics and graduated in 1877.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] While at Harvard, he was a member of the Hasty Pudding.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He graduated from Harvard Law School in 1880 and practiced law from 1880 to 1897 in partnership with his cousin, Francis Cabot Lowell, with whom he wrote *Transfer of Stock in Corporations*, which appeared in 1884.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] On June 19, 1879, while a law student, he married a distant cousin, Anna Parker Lowell in King's Chapel in Boston and honeymooned in the Western U.S.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His first scholarly publications appeared before he undertook an academic career.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] *Essays on Government* appeared in 1889, designed to counter the arguments Woodrow Wilson made in his *Congressional Government*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The two volumes of *Governments and Parties in Continental Europe* followed in 1896.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, joining his father and brother, in 1897.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1899 Lowell was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1909, he was elected to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1897, Lowell became lecturer, and in 1898, professor of government at Harvard.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His publishing career continued with the appearance of *Colonial Civil Service* in 1900, and *The Government of England* in two volumes in 1908.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In December 1901, Lowell and his wife donated funds anonymously to erect a building housing a large lecture hall, a facility the university lacked at the time.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It became the New Lecture Hall (later renamed Lowell Lecture Hall), at the corner of Oxford and Kirkland Streets, and held a 928-seat auditorium as well as 8 meeting rooms.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In the 1990s after being damaged , the hall was renovated and now has 352 seats in the main hall, and eight classrooms with capacity of 22-24 people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] From relatively early in his professional career, Lowell worried about the role of racial and ethnic minorities in American society.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] As early as 1887, he wrote of the Irish: "What we need is not to dominate the Irish, but to absorb them ...
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] We want them to become rich, and send their sons to our colleges, to share our prosperity and our sentiments.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] We do not want to feel that they are among us and yet not really part of us." He believed that only a homogeneous society could safeguard the achievements of American democracy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Sometime before 1906, he became an honorary vice-president of the Immigration Restriction League, an organization that promoted literacy tests and tightened enforcement of immigration laws.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1910, he wrote approvingly in private of excluding Chinese immigrants entirely and of Southern states that denied the franchise to black citizens.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He was an early member of the American Academy of Arts and Letters.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1909, he became president of the American Political Science Association.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] That same year, he succeeded Charles William Eliot as president of Harvard University, a post he held for 24 years until his retirement in 1933.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell received an honorary doctorate from the University of Leiden (the Netherlands) on 30 August 1919.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell immediately embarked upon a series of reforms that were both academic and social in nature.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Eliot, Harvard had replaced the single standardized undergraduate course with a system that allowed students free choice of electives.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] That was a logical extension of the trend in U.S. education that had modeled the university on the German system, including the German principle of student freedom in choosing courses.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] So dominant was Harvard's role in American education that all large American colleges and universities had adopted the elective system by 1904.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It appealed to all student types, those intellectually curious and energetic as well as the lazy without intellectual ambition.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell now implemented a second, equally revolutionary restructuring of undergraduate education.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] As early as his service on an ad hoc faculty Committee on Improving Instruction in 1903, he had determined that the elective system was a failure.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Paired with the concentration requirement was a tutorial system in which every student had the guidance of a tutor to see he was prepared for examination in his area of concentration.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] On admissions, Lowell continued Eliot's attempts to broaden the backgrounds of the entering class.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Eliot had abolished the requirement in Greek (1886) and Latin (1898) so that students from schools other than elite preparatory schools could gain entry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Educational practices were only one side of the crisis Lowell saw at Harvard.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He analyzed the social divisions of the Harvard students in similar terms.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] As the admissions process changed over the years, Lowell recognized that the student body was divided sharply socially and by class, far from the cohesive body he remembered from a few decades earlier.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Student living arrangements embodied and intensified the problem.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] That produced two classes, the underprivileged living in Harvard Yard in out-of-date buildings and the upper crust living on the "Gold Coast" of Mt.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's long-term solution was a residential system that he only achieved with the opening of the residential houses in 1930.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In the short term, Lowell raised funds and initiated construction projects that would permit the College to house all its freshmen together.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The first Freshman Halls opened in 1914.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1920, Harvard purchased the private dormitories on Mt.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1900, Lowell succeeded his father as Trustee of the Lowell Institute, which Lowell's great-grandfather founded to subsidize public lectures and popular education programs.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Throughout the 40 years he headed the Institute, Lowell's selection of topics and lecturers for the public series reflected his conservative tastes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Topics tended to history and government, with some science and music upon occasion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He ignored contemporary literature and current social trends.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Typical were "The War of 1812," "The Development of Choral Music," "The Migration of Birds," and "American Orators and Oratory." A balanced series on "Soviet Russia after Thirteen Years" was an exception.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] To the education programs Lowell brought his instinct for organization.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He transformed the earlier variety of scientific courses into the School for Industrial Foremen at MIT, later called the Lowell Institute School, and focused its program on mechanical and electrical engineering.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Stating that "any popular education at the present day should be systematic," he hired Harvard professors to repeat their courses for an audience of adults in Boston in the late afternoon or evening, promising the same quality and examinations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When he became Harvard's President, Lowell exploited his two positions to press further.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1910, he led in the formation of a consortium of area schools, soon called the Commission on Extension Courses, that included Boston University, Boston College, MIT, Simmons, Tufts, Wellesley, and the Museum of Fine Arts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] All agreed to provide similar courses and agreed to award the degree of Associate in Arts to students who completed the equivalent of a college program.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Roughly a third of the students were teachers, a third office workers, and the remainder working at home.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When the schoolteachers asked why they were not entitled to the same bachelor's degree as the Harvard College students, Lowell defended the distinction.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Though courses were comparable, the programs and requirements were different, since the many specialized courses required of the College students could not be offered in the Extension Program.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He meant the Associate in Arts degree to be distinctive.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When Lowell learned in 1933 that other American schools had begun to award the Associate in Arts degree to students after the equivalent of just two years of work, he felt betrayed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He wrote: "the name of Associate in Arts has been degraded, probably beyond recovery, by wicked, thievish, and otherwise disreputable institutions." Harvard responded with a new Adjunct in Arts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] During World War I, when American universities were under great pressure to demonstrate their unambiguous commitment to the American war effort, Harvard under Lowell established a distinguished record of independence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's uncompromising statement in support of academic freedom was a landmark event at a time when other universities were demanding compliant behavior from their faculty.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He similarly defended a student's anti-German poem with a statement of principle in defense of free speech within the academic community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1915, Kuno Meyer a professor at the University of Berlin who was considering a temporary Harvard appointment, protested the publication of an undergraduate's satirical poem in a college magazine.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell replied that freedom of speech played a different role in American universities than in their German counterparts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] During the Boston police strike of 1919, Lowell called upon Harvard's students "to help in any way ... to maintain order and support the laws of the Commonwealth" by providing security in place of the strikers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Harold Laski, a tutor in political science of socialist views and still too young to have a scholarly reputation, supported the strikers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1920, the brother of a student who had recently died by suicide brought evidence of ongoing homosexual activity among the students to the College's Acting Dean Chester N.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] After consulting with Lowell and under his authority, the Dean convened an ad hoc tribunal of administrators to investigate the charges.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It conducted more than 30 interviews behind closed doors and took action against eight students, a recent graduate, and an assistant professor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] They were expelled or had their association with the university severed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell proved particularly opposed to readmission for those who had been expelled only for associating too closely with those more directly involved.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He eventually relented in two of four cases.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] African-American students had lived in Harvard's dormitories for decades, until Lowell changed the policy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Freshmen were required to live in the Freshman Halls beginning in 1915.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Two black students did live there during World War I without incident.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When a few were excluded after the war they raised no protest.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The matter became the object of student protest in 1922, when six banned black freshmen, led by a recent alumnus who was studying at the Business School, protested their exclusion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When their direct appeal to Lowell failed, the students organized public support from alumni and the press.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Of those who wrote to Lowell, blacks saw his position as unqualified racism.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Whites either saw it as a violation of Harvard's traditions or applauded it in frankly racist terms.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Most criticism saw Lowell's stance as a submission to Southern prejudice.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One called it "the slaveholder's prejudice" and another called Lowell's policy a "surrender to the Bourbon South." One Wisconsin minister suggested Lowell allow the black students to live "voluntarily" in a segregated section of the Freshman Halls.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Roosevelt, wrote: "It seems to be a pity that the matter ever came up in this way.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Despite an official policy of integration, what freshmen experienced thereafter is not entirely clear.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Some black freshmen lived in the dormitories but believed that not all the Freshman Halls were open to them.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One was granted permission to live outside the Freshman Halls even though he had not requested such a privilege.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Harvard Dean Henry Aaron Yeomans, later Lowell's biographer, frankly admitted that he and Lowell as administrators found a way to accommodate themselves to the Overseers' stated principle: "The matter was settled in theory, and in practice no serious difficulties were encountered.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The applicant who had raised the question decided to live elsewhere.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Following Lowell's earlier reform of Harvard's admissions process to increase the admission of public school students, the Jewish proportion of the student body rose from 6% in 1908 to 22% in 1922, at a time when Jews constituted about 3% of the U.S. population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell, continuing to focus on the cohesiveness of the student body, described a campus where antisemitism was growing and Jewish students were ever more likely to be isolated from the majority.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He feared—and recent developments at Columbia University supported him—that the social elite would cease sending its sons to Harvard as Jewish enrollment increased.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He cited what he saw as the parallel experience of hotels and clubs that lost their old membership when the proportion of Jewish members increased.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He proposed limiting Jewish admissions to 15% of the entering class.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] His attempts to persuade members of the Harvard Board of Overseers to adopt his views were already failing when the plan was leaked to the *Boston Post* in May 1922.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The idea was immediately denounced by Irish and black groups and by the American Federation of Labor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell continued to argue both in private correspondence and in public speeches that his rationale was the welfare of the Jewish students.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The question was turned over to a faculty committee: the Committee on Methods of Sifting Candidates for Admission.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In the course of the internal campaign to influence that group's work, Lowell sought to exploit divisions within the Jewish community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Despite the basic divide between the older Jewish immigrants, usually of German origin, and the lower class of more recently arrived Eastern European Jews, Lowell found no ally there who would articulate his view of "desirable" and "undesirable" Jews.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The faculty committee eventually rejected Lowell's proposed quota.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Instead, Harvard's new guiding principle in admissions would be the top seventh rule.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Harvard would reach out to youths in smaller cities and towns, even to rural communities, with the guideline that the student place in the top seventh of his class.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It would seek "to pick out the best pupils from good schools, here, there, and everywhere." Though some suspected this was nothing but a covert way to decrease Jewish enrollment, the policy had the opposite effect.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The numbers of non-Jewish students attracted from the South and West could not match the larger numbers of Jews admitted from the Middle Atlantic and New England states.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] By 1925, Jews made up 28% of the entering class.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell then found another way to accomplish his goal, this time less publicly.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He first won approval from the Harvard Board of Overseers for a new policy that would, in addition to traditional academic criteria, use letters from teachers and interviews to assess an applicant's "aptitude and character," thus introducing discretion in the place of the strict top seventh rule.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] When Lowell left his position in 1933, Jews made up 10% of the undergraduate population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1916, President Woodrow Wilson nominated Louis Brandeis, a private attorney renowned as a liberal opponent of monopolies and proponent of social reform legislation, to serve as an Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] As public opinion on the nomination divided along ideological lines, Lowell joined the Republican establishment, particularly that of his Boston Brahmin class, in opposition.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He joined 54 others in signing a letter claiming that Brandeis lacked the requisite "legal temperament and capacity." An editorial in the *Harvard Alumni Bulletin* criticized him for needlessly involving the university in a political dispute.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Some students organized their own petition in favor of the nomination.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Though some opposition to Brandeis was rooted in antisemitism, Brandeis himself viewed Lowell's opposition as driven by social class prejudice.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Following the outbreak of World War I in 1914, Lowell helped found a civic organization to promote international cooperation to prevent future wars.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It was meant to be non-partisan but was inevitably drawn into partisan politics as the subject of American participation in the League of Nations dominated post-war politics.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell described himself as "an inconsistent Republican" or "an independent of Republican antecedents." By the time the debate ended, many questioned that independence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] At a convention at Philadelphia's Independence Hall on June 17, 1915, with former President William Howard Taft presiding, one hundred noteworthy Americans announced the formation of the League to Enforce Peace.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] They proposed an international agreement in which participating nations would agree to "jointly use their economic and military force against any one of their number that goes to war or commits acts of hostility against another." The founders included Alexander Graham Bell, Rabbi Stephen S.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Wise, James Cardinal Gibbons of Baltimore, and Edward Filene on behalf of the recently founded U.S.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell was elected to the Executive Committee.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The initial efforts of the League to Enforce Peace aimed at creating public awareness through magazine articles and speeches.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Then-President Wilson's specific proposal for the League of Nations met resistance from the Republican-controlled Senate and the opposition led by Senator Henry Cabot Lodge of Massachusetts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell watched the high-minded debate deteriorate until the ideal of international cooperation was "sacrificed to party intrigue, personal antipathy, and pride of authorship." Lowell and the League to Enforce Peace tried to hold the middle ground.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He cared little about Wilson's specific plan or the details of the reservations or amendments Lodge wanted to attach for the Senate to give its assent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell believed American participation was the greater goal, the exact nature of the organization secondary.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One of the most widely publicized confrontations saw Lowell debate Lodge, the League's most prominent opponent, in Boston's Symphony Hall on March 19, 1919, with Massachusetts Governor Calvin Coolidge presiding.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] That debate proved gentlemanly, since Lowell believed that the resolution of the policy dispute required Wilson and Lodge to compromise.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell had sharper exchanges with the die-hard Republican isolationist Senator William Borah of Idaho.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell repeatedly argued that George Washington's Farewell Address and its stricture against entangling alliances held no relevance for the present.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Senator Borah saw a lack of patriotism: "There are a vast number of people supporting the league of nations who never let an opportunity go by of belittling ... everything that is truly American: and Dr.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In the summer of 1919, the League to Enforce Peace published a book of essays modeled on the Federalist Papers called *The Covenanter: An American Exposition of the Covenant of the League of Nations*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] As the election of 1920 approached, the Republican nominee, Warren Harding, campaigned on the domestic issues that united his party and sent confusing signals about his support for a League of Nations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] With the election just weeks away, whole groups of League proponents chose different sides.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One entire organization of independent voters chose James Cox, the Democratic candidate, who favored the League but showed no more flexibility than President Wilson.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell and many other prominent League supporters backed Harding, publishing a statement that became known as the "Letter of the 31 Republicans" on October 14, 1920.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell could not express his reasoning publicly.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In his view, the League's proponents, and especially the League's Republican proponents, needed to control public perception of Harding's victory, which everyone knew was certain.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] They could not allow the election to appear as a victory of anti-League Republicans over pro-League Democrats.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] If the League lost a referendum in that way, there would be no hope for its revival under the new administration.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The claim in the "Statement of 31 Republicans" that a Harding victory meant brighter prospects for the League of Nations was badly received by some League proponents.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell came in for attack precisely because of his earlier claims to independence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One Harvard graduate, who had just formed the New Hampshire committee to raise funds for the University's endowment, wrote: "One can understand a Republican partisan and respect him.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] One can understand a Democratic partisan and respect him.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Harding as president disappointed proponents of the League, but Lowell never regretted his decision to endorse him.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He did view the work of the League to Enforce Peace more critically.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Its oratory had failed to engage the public at large, he thought, so public opinion remained "indifferent" to its call for muscular internationalism, leaving isolation or at least inaction to win the day.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1927, Massachusetts Governor Alvan T.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Fuller was facing last minute appeals to grant clemency to Sacco and Vanzetti, whose case had attracted attention worldwide.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He appointed Lowell to an Advisory Committee along with President Samuel Wesley Stratton of MIT and Probate Judge Robert Grant.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] They were tasked with reviewing the trial of Sacco and Vanzetti to determine whether the trial had been fair.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's appointment was generally well received, for though he had controversy in his past he had also at times demonstrated an independent streak.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] The defense attorneys considered resigning when they determined that the Committee was biased against the defendants, but some of the defendants' most prominent supporters, including Harvard Law Professor Felix Frankfurter and Judge Julian W.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] After two weeks of hearing witnesses and reviewing evidence, the trio produced a report largely authored by Lowell that criticized the judge in the case but deemed the trial fair.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] A defense attorney later noted ruefully that the release of the Committee's report "abruptly stilled the burgeoning doubts among the leaders of opinion in New England." Supporters of the convicted men denounced the Committee.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Harold Laski said the decision represented Lowell's "loyalty to his class." The affair dogged Lowell for the rest of his life.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In 1936, on the day when Harvard's 300th anniversary was celebrated, 28 Harvard alumni attacked Lowell for his role in the case, including editor Malcolm Cowley, scholar Newton Arvin, and author John Dos Passos.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's health declined slowly and his lifelong hearing problems worsened.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He resigned his position as Harvard's president on November 21, 1932, and served through the following summer.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] During his years as president, enrollment at the College expanded from 3,000 to 8,000 and its endowment grew from $23 to $123 million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's construction projects, some based on the Freshman Halls and the College system, but including Widener Library, the Memorial Church and many others, had transformed the university's infrastructure.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Also among the new campus buildings of Lowell's tenure was the President's House (later called Loeb House) at 17 Quincy Street, which Lowell commissioned from his cousin Guy Lowell.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] It remained the residence of succeeding Harvard Presidents until 1971.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell is remembered as well for a donation of one million dollars to help found the Harvard Society of Fellows.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Years before, he had given $10,500 to purchase a 13-inch telescope for his deceased brother Percival's Lowell Observatory, which in 1930 gained fame as the Pluto Discovery Telescope.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell's wife of 51 years, Anna Parker Lowell, died in the spring of 1930.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In retirement from Harvard, he lived on Marlborough Street in Boston's Back Bay and in Cotuit on Cape Cod.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He owned Conaumet Neck along the shores of Mashpee Pond.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] In his will, he bequeathed land along the pond to The Trustees of Reservations, which maintains it as the Lowell Holly Reservation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He headed the Boston Municipal Research Bureau and chaired a Committee on the Reform of Judicial Procedure under the auspices of the Boston Chamber of Commerce.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He also became head of the Motion Picture Research Council, a group established to promote studies of the social values of motion pictures.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He published frequently in such periodicals as *The Atlantic* and *Foreign Affairs*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Lowell was an honorary member of the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati and was invested with the Grand Cross of the Legion of Honor of France.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] He died at home on Marlborough Street on January 6, 1943.
[src:charles-william-eliot/a-lawrence-lowell] Funeral services were held at Harvard's Memorial Church.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In British and Australian/New Zealand English, "faculty" usually refers to a sub-division of a university (usually the teaching/research staff of one or a group of departments).
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In contrast, in North America "faculty" refers to the people who teach and research, and is distinguished from "staff", who are hired in administrative, operations, and support roles.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] For example the *Faculty Handbook* at Boston University defines faculty as Assistant, Associate, and Full Professors, those with professorial titles modified by “Research,” “Clinical,” and “of the Practice, Lecturers of all ranks, and Instructors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In the United States and parts of Canada, universities, community colleges and even some secondary and primary schools use the term *faculty*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] Other institutions (e.g., teaching hospitals or not-for-profit research institutes) may likewise use the term *faculty*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In parts of the US, the term *academic staff* can be synonymous with just *staff*, which instead refers to staff that is not primarily involved with teaching or research.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] The higher education regulatory body of India, University Grants Commission, defines academic staff as teachers, librarians, and physical education personnel.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In countries like the Philippines, faculty is used more broadly to refer to teaching staff of either a basic or higher education institution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In many universities, the members of the administration (e.g., department chairs, deans, vice presidents, presidents, and librarians) are also faculty members; many of them begin (and remain) as professors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] These two types of faculty members are sometimes known as "nine-month faculty" and "twelve-month faculty".
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] Faculty who are paid a nine-month salary are typically allowed to seek external funds from grant agencies to partially or fully support their research activities during the summer months.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] Librarians are a special case in that they are educators like faculty who belong to degree granting departments, not necessarily administrators who have management responsibilities like Deans, Presidents, and Vice Presidents.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] Most university faculty members hold a Ph.D. or equivalent highest-level degree in their field.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] Some professionals or instructors from other institutions who are associated with a particular university (e.g., by teaching some courses or supervising graduate students) but do not hold professorships may be appointed as adjunct faculty.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] In North America, faculty is a distinct category from staff, although members of both groups are employees of the institution in question.
[src:charles-william-eliot/academic-staff] This is distinct from, for example, the British (and European, Australia, and New Zealand) usage, in which all employees of the institution are staff either on academic or professional (i.e. non-academic) contracts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park contains the tallest mountain on the Atlantic Coast of the United States (Cadillac Mountain), exposed granite domes, glacial erratics, U-shaped valleys, and cobble beaches.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Its mountains, lakes, streams, wetlands, forests, meadows, and coastlines contribute to a diversity of plants and animals.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Woven into this landscape is a historic carriage road system financed by John D.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Acadia has a rich human history, dating back more than 10,000 years ago with the Wabanaki people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The 17th century brought fur traders and other European explorers, while the 19th century saw an influx of summer visitors, then wealthy families.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Many conservation-minded citizens, among them George B.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Dorr (the "Father of Acadia National Park"), worked to establish this first U.S. national park east of the Mississippi River and the only one in the Northeastern United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Acadia was initially designated Sieur de Monts National Monument by proclamation of President Woodrow Wilson in 1916, then renamed and redesignated Lafayette National Park in 1919.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park was renamed Acadia National Park in 1929.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Winter activities include cross-country skiing, snowshoeing, snowmobiling, and ice fishing.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Two campgrounds are located on Mount Desert Island, another campground is on the Schoodic Peninsula, and five lean-to sites are on Isle au Haut.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The main visitor center is at Hulls Cove, northwest of Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Park visitation has been steadily increasing in Acadia over the past decade, with 2021 seeing a record count of 4.07 million visitors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In 2023 the park saw 3,879,890 recreational visitors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park includes mountains, an ocean coastline, woodlands, lakes, and ponds.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Bar Island, which can be visited on foot over a sandbar around low tide, and the Porcupine Islands are in Frenchman Bay by Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] About 57 mi (92 km) of carriage roads were designed and financed by John D.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Rockefeller Jr. on Mount Desert Island, 45 miles (72 km) of which continue to be maintained inside the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] As of 2015, the permanent park boundary, as established by act of Congress in 1986, included 12,416 acres (5,025 ha; 19.400 sq mi; 50.25 km2) of privately owned land under conservation easements managed by the National Park Service, which plans to acquire the land at some point.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The mountains of Acadia National Park overlook the Atlantic Ocean, island lakes, and pine forests.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Twenty-six significant mountains rise in the park, ranging from 284 ft (87 m) at Flying Mountain's summit to 1,530 ft (470 m) at Cadillac Mountain's summit.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Cadillac Mountain, named after the French explorer Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac, is on the eastern side of the island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Cadillac is the tallest mountain along the eastern coastline of the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The summit of Cadillac is the first place in the United States where one may watch the sunrise from October 7 through March 6, due to its eastern location and height.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The 27-mile (43 km) Park Loop Road leads to many scenic viewpoints along the coast, through forests and to the top of Cadillac Mountain.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Some of the island's west side features include Echo Lake and beach (a designated freshwater swimming area), Acadia Mountain, Beech Mountain, Long Pond, and Seal Cove Pond.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Bass Harbor Head Light is situated atop a cliff on the southernmost tip of the west side of the island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Baker Island Light and Bear Island Light are the other two lighthouses managed by Acadia.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Somes Sound is a five-mile (8 km) long fjard formed during a glacial period that nearly divides the island in half.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The sound is 130 ft (40 m) deep at its deepest point, and is bordered by Norumbega Mountain to the east, and Acadia Mountain and Saint Sauveur Mountain to the west.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The towns of Southwest Harbor and Northeast Harbor face one another across the inlet to Somes Sound.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Native Americans have inhabited the area called Acadia for at least 12,000 years, including the coastal areas of Maine, Canada, and adjacent islands.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Wabanaki Confederacy ("People of the Dawnland") consists of five related Algonquian nations—the Maliseet, Mi'kmaq, Passamaquoddy, Abenaki and Penobscot.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Some of the nations call Mount Desert Island *Pemetic* ("range of mountains"), which has remained at the center of the Wabanaki traditional ancestral homeland and territory of traditional stewardship responsibility to the present day.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The etymology of the park's name begins with the Mi'kmaq term *akadie* ("piece of land") which was rendered as *l'Acadie* by French explorers, and translated into English as Acadia.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Wabanaki traveled to the island in birch bark canoes to hunt, fish, gather berries, harvest clams and basket-making resources like sweetgrass, and to trade with other Wabanakis.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] They camped near places like Somes Sound.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In the early 17th century, Asticou was the chieftain of the greater Mount Desert Island area, one district of an intertribal confederacy known as Mawooshen led by the grandchief Bashaba.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Castine (*Pentagoet* in the native language) was the grandchief's favored rendezvous site for the Wabanaki tribes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The site is located just west of Mount Desert Island at the mouth of the Bagaduce River in eastern Penobscot Bay.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] From 1615, Castine developed into a major fur trading post where French, English, and Dutch traders all fought for control.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Sealskins, moose hides, and furs were traded by the Wabanakis for European commodities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] By the early 1620s, warfare and introduced diseases, including smallpox, cholera and influenza, had decimated the tribes from Mount Desert Island southward to Cape Cod, leaving about 10 percent of the original population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The border established between the United States and Canada after the American Revolution split the Wabanaki homelands.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The confederacy was dissolved around 1870 due to pressure from the American and Canadian governments, though the tribal nations continued to interact in their traditional ways.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In the nineteenth century, Wabanakis sold handmade ash and birch bark baskets to travelers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Wabanaki performed dances for summer tourists and residents at Sieur de Monts and the town of Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Wabanaki guides led canoe trips around Frenchman Bay and the Cranberry Islands.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] For two years, 1970–71, the nations operated a Wabanaki educational center called T.R.I.B.E.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] (Teaching and Research in Bicultural Education) on the west side of Eagle Lake.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] American Indian land claims in Maine were legally settled in 1980 and 1991.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The annual Bar Harbor Native American Festival began in 1989, jointly sponsored by the tribes and the Abbe Museum.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Maine Indian Basketmakers Alliance was formed in 1993, assisting in the coordination of the annual festival with the museum.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Currently, each tribe has a reservation and government headquarters located within their territories throughout Maine.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Some Wabanakis live on Mount Desert Island, while others visit for board meetings at the Abbe Museum, to advise on and perform in exhibitions, for craft demonstrations, and to gather sweetgrass and sell handmade baskets at the annual festival.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Italian explorer Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed along the coast of Mount Desert Island during an expedition for the French Crown in 1524.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] He was followed by Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese explorer for the Spanish Crown in 1525.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] French explorer Jean Alfonse arrived in 1542.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Alfonse entered Penobscot Bay and recorded details about the fur trade.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Portuguese navigator Simon Ferdinando guided an English expedition in 1580.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A few hundred people were living on Mount Desert Island when Samuel de Champlain arrived in 1604.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Two Wabanakis led Champlain to Mount Desert Island, which he named Isle des Monts Deserts (Island of Barren Mountains) due to its barren peaks; he named Isle au Haut (High Island) due to its height.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The first French missionary colony in America was established on Mount Desert Island in 1613.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The colony was destroyed a short time later by an armed vessel from the Colony of Virginia as the first act of overt warfare in the long struggle leading to the French and Indian Wars.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The island was granted to Antoine de la Mothe Cadillac by King Louis XIV in 1688, but ceded to Great Britain in 1713 as part of the Peace of Utrecht.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Massachusetts governor Sir Francis Bernard, 1st Baronet, assumed control of the island in 1760.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In 1790, Massachusetts granted the eastern half of the island to Cadillac's granddaughter, Mme. de Gregoire, while Bernard's son John retained ownership of the western half.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The first record of summer visitors vacationing on the island was in 1855, and steamboat service from Boston was inaugurated in 1868.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Green Mountain Cog Railway was built from the shore of Eagle Lake to the summit of Cadillac Mountain in 1888.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In 1901, the Maine Legislature granted Hancock County a charter to acquire and hold land on the island in the public interest.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Artists and journalists had revealed and popularized the island in the mid-1800s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Painters came from the Hudson River School, including Thomas Cole and Frederic Church, inspiring patrons and friends to visit.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The term *rusticator* was used to describe these early visitors who stayed in the homes of local fishermen and farmers for modest fees.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The accommodations soon became insufficient for the increasing amount of summer visitors, and by 1880, thirty hotels were operating on the island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Tourism was becoming the major industry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] For a select few Americans, the 1880s and the Gay Nineties meant affluence on a scale without precedent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mount Desert Island, being remote from the cities of the east, became a summer retreat for families such as the Rockefellers, Morgans, Fords, Vanderbilts, Carnegies, and Astors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] These families, with the help of developers such as Charles T.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] How, constructed elegant estates, which they called cottages.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Luxury, refinement, and large gatherings replaced the buckboard rides, picnics, and day-long hikes of the rusticators.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] For more than forty years, the wealthy dominated summer activity on Mount Desert Island, but the Great Depression and World War II brought an end to the extravagance.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The landscape architect Charles Eliot is credited with the idea for the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Dorr, called the "Father of Acadia National Park", along with Eliot's father Charles W.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Eliot (president of Harvard from 1869 to 1909), supported the idea both through donations of land and through advocacy at the state and federal levels.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Dorr later served as the park's first superintendent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] President Woodrow Wilson first established its federal status as Sieur de Monts National Monument on July 8, 1916, administered by the National Park Service.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] It was the first national park created from private lands gifted to the public.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Dorr, 1916, *Acadia National Park: Its Origin and Background* (1942), pp.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Congress redesignated the national monument as Lafayette National Park on February 26, 1919, the first American national park east of the Mississippi River and the only one in the Northeastern United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park was named after the Marquis de Lafayette, an influential French participant in the American Revolution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Jordan Pond Road was started in 1922 and completed as a scenic motor highway in 1927.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Cadillac Mountain Summit Road, begun in 1925, was completed in 1931.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The name of the park was changed to Acadia National Park on January 19, 1929, in honor of the former French colony of Acadia, which once included Maine.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In 1929 Schoodic Peninsula was donated to Acadia by John Godfrey Moore's second wife Louise and daughters Ruth and Faith.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Keeping up with the taxes on the Schoodic land became a drain on the family finances and they thought this would be a fitting way to honor John Godfrey Moore.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] There was an unspoken stipulation in the discussions — the heirs were anglophiles that did not want to have their land as part of Lafayette National Park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Conservationist George Dorr suggested the name Acadia, and the deal went through after the name changed, ensuring the expansion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] From 1915 to 1940, the wealthy philanthropist John D.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Rockefeller Jr. financed, designed, and directed the construction of a network of carriage roads throughout the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] He sponsored the landscape architect Beatrix Farrand, whose family owned a summer home in Bar Harbor named Reef Point Estate, to design the planting plans for the carriage roads (c.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The network originally encompassed about 57 miles (92 km) of crushed stone carriage roads with 17 stone-faced, steel-reinforced concrete bridges (16 financed by Rockefeller), and two gate lodges—one at Jordan Pond and the other near Northeast Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] About 45 miles (72 km) of carriage roads are maintained and accessible within park boundaries.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Granite coping stones along carriage road edges act as guard rails; they are nicknamed "Rockefeller's Teeth".
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The carriage roads are open from the end of the spring mud season, generally in late April, through the summer, autumn, and winter months, until the following spring thaw causes another closure in March to prevent damage to the gravel surface.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Acadia National Park's first naturalist, Arthur Stupka, also had the distinction of being the first NPS naturalist to serve in any of the NPS's eastern United States districts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] He joined the park staff in 1932, and in the capacity of park naturalist he wrote, edited and published a four-volume serial entitled *Nature Notes from Acadia* (1932–1935).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Beginning on October 17, 1947, more than 10,000 acres (4,000 ha; 16 sq mi; 40 km2) of Acadia National Park burned in a fire that also destroyed an additional 7,000 acres (2,800 ha; 11 sq mi; 28 km2) of Mount Desert Island outside the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The fire began along Crooked Road west of Hulls Cove (northwest of Bar Harbor).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The forest fire was one of a series of fires that consumed much of Maine's forest in a dry year.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The fire burned until November 14, and was fought by the Coast Guard, Army Air Corps, Navy, local residents, and National Park Service employees from around the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Sixty-seven of the historic summer cottages along Millionaires' Row, along with 170 other homes, and five hotels were destroyed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Restoration of the park was substantially supported by the Rockefeller family.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Regrowth has occurred naturally with new deciduous forests consisting of birch and aspen enhancing the colors of autumn foliage, adding diversity to tree populations, and providing for the eventual regeneration of spruce and fir forests.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The region is characterized by a large seasonal variation in temperature with warm to hot summers that are often humid, and cold to severely cold winters.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] According to the Köppen climate classification system, Mount Desert Island has a warm-summer humid continental climate (*Dfb*).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The average annual temperature in the park is 47.3 °F (8.5 °C).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] July is the warmest month with an average of 69.7 °F (20.9 °C), while January is the coldest month with an average of 23.8 °F (−4.6 °C).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The record high and low temperatures are 96 °F (36 °C) and −21 °F (−29 °C), respectively.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The plant hardiness zone is 5b with an average annual extreme minimum air temperature of −11.4 °F (−24.1 °C).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Average annual precipitation in Bar Harbor is 55.54" (1411 mm).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] November is the wettest month with 5.89" (150 mm) of precipitation on average, while July is the driest month with 3.27" (83 mm).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Precipitation days are spread evenly throughout the year with December averaging the most days with about 14, while August averages the least with about 9.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The annual average days with precipitation is 139.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Snow has been recorded from October to May, although the majority falls from December to March.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The snowiest month is January with 18.3" (46 cm), and the annual average is 66.1" (167 cm).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Cadillac Mountain Intrusive Complex is part of the Coastal Maine Magmatic Province, consisting of over a hundred mafic and felsic plutons associated with the Acadian Orogeny.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mount Desert Island bedrock consists mainly of Cadillac Mountain granite.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Perthite gives the granite its pinkish color.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Silurian age granite ranges from 424 to 419 million years ago (Mya).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Diabase dikes trend north–south through the complex.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Almost 300 million years of erosion followed before the deposition of glacial features during the Pleistocene.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Glacial polish, glacial striations, and chatter marks are evident in granitic surfaces.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Other glacier-shaped features include The Bubbles (two rôche moutonnées) and the U-shaped valleys of Sargent Mountain Pond, Jordan Pond, Seal Cove Pond, Long Pond, Echo Lake, and Eagle Lake.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Somes Sound is a fjard and terminal moraines form the southern end of Long Pond, Echo Lake, and Jordan Pond.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Bubble Rock is an example of a glacial erratic.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] More than 500 Mya, layers of mud, sand and volcanic ash were buried beneath the ocean where high pressure, heat and tectonic activity created a metamorphic rock formation called the Ellsworth Schist.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] White and gray quartz, feldspar, and green chlorite comprise the schist, which is the oldest rock in the Mount Desert Island region.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Erosion and shifting of tectonic plates eventually brought the schist to the surface.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] About 450 Mya, an ancient continental fragment, or micro-terrane, called Avalonia collided with North America.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The collision buried the schist along with accumulations of sand and silt, creating the Bar Harbor Formation which consists of brown and gray sandstone and siltstone layers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Material from volcanic flows and ash were also deposited on the formation, creating the volcanic rock found on the Cranberry Islands.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Further volcanic activity introduced igneous rocks into the Bar Harbor Formation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] As the igneous intrusions cooled, crystallized minerals formed including a gabbro composed of dark, iron-rich minerals.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mount Desert Island granite was created about 420 Mya, with one of the oldest granite bodies being Cadillac Mountain, the largest on the island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The granite body rose slowly through bedrock, fracturing it into large pieces, some of which melted under intense heat.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] As the granite cooled, the bedrock fragments were left surrounded by crystallized granite in a shatter zone that is visible on the eastern side of the mountain.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A fine-grained, black igneous rock called diabase intruded into the granite during later volcanic activity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Diabase bodies, or dikes, are visible along the Cadillac Mountain road and on the Schoodic Peninsula.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] During the next several hundred million years, the rock layers that still covered the large granite bodies, along with softer rock surrounding the granite, were worn away by erosion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] During the last two to three million years, a series of ice sheets flowed and receded across northern North America, eroding mountains and creating U-shaped valleys.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The glacier that covered Mount Desert Range, part of which is now called Mount Desert Island, was one mile (1.6 km) thick and moved at the rate of a few yards (meters) per year.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The mountain range was heavily eroded by the glacier which rounded off mountaintops, carved saddles, deepened valleys, and created the fjard known as Somes Sound, nearly dividing the current island in half.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Evidence of the last glacial period, the Wisconsin glaciation from about 75,000 to 11,000 years ago, is visible as long scratches, or striations, and crescent-shaped gouges created by material carried along at the base of the ice.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] As the climate warmed, the glaciers melted and receded, leaving boulders that had been carried 20 mi (32 km) or further south from their original locations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] These boulders, or glacial erratics, lie in valleys and on mountaintops, including Bubble Rock on the South Bubble.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The coastal areas of Maine sank slightly under the extreme weight of the ice sheets, allowing seawater to cover lowlands thus forming the present-day islands.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Evidence of sea caves and past beaches can be found about 300 ft (91 m) above current sea level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] As the ice receded and the land stabilized, lakes and ponds formed in valleys dammed by glacial debris.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Rivers and streams flowed again through the watershed, continuing the gradual erosion of the drainage paths.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Acadia has a coastline composed of rocky headlands, and more heavily eroded stony or sandy beaches.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Coastal areas directly facing the wind-driven waves of the Atlantic Ocean are solely composed of large boulders as all other material has been washed out to sea.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Areas partially protected by rocky headlands contain the remains of more eroded rocks, consisting of pebbles, cobbles and smaller boulders.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Sheltered coves, such as at Sand Beach, contain fine-grained particles that are primarily the remains of shells and other hard parts of marine life, including mussels and sea urchins.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Granitic ridges are subjected to frost weathering.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Joints, or fractures, are slowly enlarged as trapped water repeatedly freezes and melts, eventually splitting off a block.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Bright pink scars with granitic rubble below are evidence of such weathering; one example can be seen above the Tarn, a pond just south of Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] At least twelve sea caves are located in several coastal areas of the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Sea caves are formed when waves cause erosion of coastal rock formations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] If a sea cave is enlarged enough, it may break through a headland to form a sea arch.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Frequent thawing in winter prevents large accumulations of snow, and keeps the ground well saturated.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Ice storms are common in winter and early spring, while rain occurs throughout the year.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Saturated soils, thawing, and heavy precipitation lead to rockfalls every spring along Mount Desert Island's loop road, as well as slumping along coastal bluffs.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mass wasting (slope movement) of marine clay, deposited when the sea level was much higher, occurs along Hunters Brook on Mount Desert Island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Slumping of the greenish-gray clay destabilized the bank, changing the course of the stream.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The eastern end of Otter Cove's beach contains eroded gullies of marine clay.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mass wasting and slope failure may occur wherever marine clay is exposed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Earthquakes with epicenters near the park have caused landslides, damaging roads and trails.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Earthquakes in Maine occur at a low but steady rate, with magnitudes usually less than 4.8 on the Richter scale.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Presumpscot Formation has yielded a diverse collection of mostly marine fossils.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The formation is composed of silt and clay deposited between 15 and 11,000 years ago when isostatic loading raised sea level as land was submerged to about 330–395 ft (101–120 m) above the current level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Post-glacial rebound lowered sea level, exposing the seabed to a depth of about 195 ft (59 m) below the current level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A global rise in sea-level flooded the shelf to the current level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Plant fossils include pollen, spores, logs, and other plant macrofossils.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Invertebrate fossils include foraminifera (protists that form test shells), sponge spicules, bryozoans, bivalves, gastropods, *Spirorbis*, beetles, ants, barnacles, decapod crustaceans (crabs, shrimp, lobsters, etc.), ostracodes (seed shrimp), and ophiuroids (brittle stars).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Vertebrate fossils include fish and a few rare large mammals, such as walruses, whales, and a mammoth.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Walrus remains have been reported on Andrews Island, 19 mi (31 km) west of Isle au Haut; Addison Point, 23 mi (37 km) northeast of the Schoodic Peninsula; and Gardiner, 57 mi (92 km) west-northwest of Isle au Haut.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The mammoth bones were found at Scarborough, 87 mi (140 km) southwest of Isle au Haut.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Tiny subalpine plants grow in the granite joints on mountaintops and on the downwind side of rocks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Stunted, gnarled trees also survive near the summits.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Spruce-fir boreal forests cover much of the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Stands of oak, maple, beech, and other hardwoods more typical of New England represent the eastern deciduous forest. pitch pines and scrub oaks inhabit isolated forests at their northeastern range limit, while jack pines reach the southern limit of their range in Acadia.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Fourteen great ponds and ten smaller ponds provide habitat for many fish and waterfowl species.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] More than 20% of the park is classified as wetland.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Marshes and swamps form the transition between terrestrial and aquatic environments, maintaining biodiversity by providing a habitat for a wide range of species.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Native wildlife frequent wetlands alongside species that are nesting, overwintering or migrating, such as birds along the Atlantic Flyway.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Wetlands are composed of 37.5% marine (sea water), 31.6% palustrine (stagnant water), 20% estuarine (coastal, brackish water), 10.7% lacustrine (freshwater lakes and ponds), and 0.2% riverine (flowing streams).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Approximately 53.6 mi (86.3 km) of perennial streams and 47.3 mi (76.1 km) of intermittent streams flow through the park, while about 50 mi (80 km) of shoreline surround 110 lakes and ponds encompassing 1,056.56 acres (427.57 ha; 1.65088 sq mi; 4.2757 km2).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Intertidal flora and fauna inhabit more than 60 mi (97 km) of rocky coastline.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The nutrient-rich marine waters cover the intertidal plants and animals twice a day.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Pools of calm water form among the rocks around low tides, inhabited by starfish, dog whelks, blue mussels, sea cucumbers, and rockweed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Flora common to both deciduous and coniferous woodlands include lowbush blueberry, Canadian bunchberry, hobblebush, bluebead lily, Canada mayflower, wild sarsaparilla, shadbush, starflower, rosy twisted stalk, wintergreen, and white pine trees.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Coniferous forest trees include the balsam fir, eastern hemlock, red pine, red spruce, and white spruce.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park has a potential natural vegetation of northeastern spruce/fir within temperate coniferous forests, according to the original A.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Spruce-fir forests cover more than sixty percent of the naturally vegetated habitats in the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Other coniferous forest plants include dewdrop, mountain holly, pinesap, one-flowered pyrola, shinleaf, trailing arbutus, northern woodsorrel, and drooping woodreed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] At least two species of invasive insect have been confirmed on trees in the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Red pine scale was confirmed on dying red pines on the south side of Norumbega Mountain near Lower Hadlock Pond in 2014.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Hemlock woolly adelgid was first found near Northeast Harbor in 2022, and has since spread to Sieur de Monts and the A Murray Young Path.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Deciduous forest trees include the white ash, big-toothed and trembling aspen, American beech, paper and yellow birch, red oak, American mountain ash, as well as mountain, red, striped, and sugar maples.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Other deciduous forest plants include large-leaved aster, chokecherry, red-berried elder, Christmas fern, threeleaf goldthread, early saxifrage, false Solomon's seal, small Solomon's seal, and twinflower.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Trees commonly found in the mountains and dry, rocky places of the national park include gray birch, common juniper, jack pine, and pitch pine, while smaller trees, or shrub, species include green alder and pin cherry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Poverty oatgrass is the most common grass found in mountainous terrain.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Freshwater marsh and pond plants include common arrowhead, horned bladderwort, highbush blueberry, bluejoint, common cattail, water lobelia, pickerelweed, marsh St.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] John's wort, swamp candles, swamp rose, white turtlehead, fragrant water-lily, and yellow water-lily.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Mount Desert Island section of the park harbors more than half of the vascular plant species occurring in Maine.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Plant, algal, and fungal specimens collected during research activities at the park are deposited for future study at a herbarium jointly administered by the park and the College of the Atlantic.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A special garden called *The Wild Gardens of Acadia* was established in the Sieur de Monts area of the park in 1961 and has since grown to include more than 400 indigenous plant species found throughout all park areas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park's wide variety of natural habitats provides homes for many different animal species.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The coastal location also encourages a large number of species; however, the small size and isolation of these habitats from mainland habitats limits the types of animals, especially their size.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Smaller animals are better adapted to smaller habitats which makes them more common and easily observed than larger ones such as black bears and moose.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] and a solitary native hare species, the snowshoe hare.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Seven reptilian species live in the park including five snakes (milk, smooth green, redbelly, eastern garter, and the ring-necked snake) and two turtles (the common snapping turtle and the eastern painted turtle).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Eleven amphibian species inhabit the park including the American toad, five frog species (bullfrog, spring peeper, green, pickerel, and wood frog), four salamander species (spotted, dusky, northern two-lined, and four-toed salamander), and the eastern newt.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The most abundant fish are the American eel, golden shiner, banded killifish, and pumpkinseed, while commonly found fish include alewife, white sucker, northern redbelly dace, chain pickerel (non-native), three-spined stickleback, nine-spined stickleback, rainbow smelt, and brook trout.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Thirteen other fish species (ten non-native) are listed by the NPS as uncommon, while eight other species are listed with an unknown abundance.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Many marine species may be observed in the surrounding waters, including seals and whales, from a sea kayak or other personal watercraft, or on ranger-narrated boat cruises.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Special whale-watching excursions launch from Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A total of 215 bird species, including migratory birds, are present at some time during the year.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] An additional 116 species are possibly present but unconfirmed, making a total of 331 potential species.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Thirty-three other bird species are considered historical and no longer present in the park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Large birds include golden and bald eagles, gyrfalcons, turkey vultures, ospreys, cormorants, and various herons, hawks, and owls.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Waterfowl species include four geese (Canada, brant, snow, and greater white-fronted geese), along with various ducks including mallards, wood ducks, pintails, wigeons, blue-winged and green-winged teals, canvasbacks, buffleheads, eiders, goldeneyes, and harlequin ducks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Seabirds include terns and four gull species (herring, laughing, ring-billed, and great black-backed gulls), while shorebirds include avocets, sandpipers and plovers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Songbirds are represented by various species of blackbirds, chickadees, finches, jays, sparrows, swallows, thrushes, vireos, warblers, and wrens.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] One of the more unique songbirds is the red crossbill, a finch that uses its crossed mandibles to efficiently extract the seeds from conifer cones, especially those of spruces, hemlocks, and pines.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The crossbills feed their young with the same seeds, rather than the insects which other species feed to their chicks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In 1991, peregrine falcons had a successful nesting in Acadia for the first time since 1956.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] At least one pair and as many as four pairs have produced offspring over the years since 1991, totaling more than 160 chicks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Many of those chicks were banded to learn about migration, habitat use, and longevity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Banded falcons have been observed as far away as Vermont, Maryland, Washington, D.C., and New Brunswick.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Beginning in early spring and continuing into mid-summer, certain trails may be closed to avoid disturbance to falcon nesting areas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Jordan Cliffs Trail, Valley Cove Trail, Precipice Trail, and a portion of the Orange and Black Path were closed from April 13 to July 13, 2018.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The same trails were closed from March 22 to August 3, 2017.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Motor vehicle touring along the 27-mile (43 km) Park Loop Road begins on April 15, if weather permits, and ends on December 1, unless significant snowfall closes it sooner.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A two-mile (3.2 km) stretch of the Ocean Drive portion of the loop, from Schooner Head Road to Sand Beach and Otter Cliff, is plowed and open all year, as is Jordan Pond Road.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The coastline can be explored on guided boat trips or by sea kayak.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Canoeing and kayaking are popular activities on accessible lakes and ponds.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] About 125 mi (201 km) of hiking trails traverse forests and mountains, while 45 mi (72 km) of carriage roads can be hiked or bicycled (motorized vehicles, including electric bikes, are prohibited).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Both the 3.5-mile long Dorr Mountain Trail and the 4.5-mile (7.2 km) long Sargent Mountain Trail are listed as National Recreation Trails.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Horseback riding is permitted on carriage roads and certain other park areas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Climbing is popular at 60 ft (18 m) high Otter Cliff, and at Great Head, Precipice, and South Bubble.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Sand Beach offers seawater swimming and Echo Lake Beach offers freshwater swimming.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] In summer, ocean water temperature ranges from 50–60 °F (10–16 °C) while lake and pond temperatures range from 55–70 °F (13–21 °C).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Ranger-led programs from mid-May to mid-October introduce visitors to the park's diverse natural and cultural history.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Park rangers offer short walks, longer hikes, boat cruises, evening amphitheater programs, and children's programs, as well as viewing of peregrine falcons and raptors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Winter activities include hiking on trails using snowshoes, or traction footwear, and trekking poles, cross-country skiing on carriage roads, snowmobiling on the paved loop road, and ice fishing on frozen ponds and lakes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mount Desert Island has two NPS campgrounds, constructed mainly by the Civilian Conservation Corps in the 1930s along with various park trails.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Blackwoods Campground is located on the east side of the island, closer to the most popular sites, the carriage roads, and Bar Harbor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Seawall Campground is on the less crowded west side of the island.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Schoodic Woods on the Schoodic Peninsula is the newest NPS campground, opened in 2015.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Five lean-to shelters are available by advance reservation at Duck Harbor Campground on Isle au Haut.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Blackwoods is open throughout the year, though only primitive walk-in camping by permit is possible in winter (December–March), while the others are open from late spring (mid-to-late May) to early autumn (late September to mid-October).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Mount Desert Island also has eleven private campgrounds outside park boundaries, while two private campgrounds are on the Schoodic Peninsula, and one is on Isle au Haut.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The park hosts the annual Acadia Night Sky Festival, attracting speakers, researchers, photographers, and artists to the area.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Park attendance increased to 3.53 million in 2018, setting a new record for the second year in a row.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The seasonal nature of the park means a concentration of visitors in the summer months that is beyond the capacity of park infrastructure.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Congestion leads to lack of available parking and gridlock, requiring road closures.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Traffic management places a toll on available rangers, competing with rescue operations that also see a sharp increase on peak attendance days.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The Island Explorer bus system is offered in part to reduce congestion; it has served 7.7 million passengers since it began operations in 1999.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A portion of park entrance fees partially funds the service.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Since the park's founding in 1916, climate change has lengthened the growing season by nearly two months.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] A longer growing season threatens native plants and invites invasive species that thrive in the longer, warmer summer season.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] An expanded warm season also lengthens the tourism season, placing further strain on park resources.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Changes in rainfall patterns have also taxed park infrastructure, increasing the maintenance required to control erosion and protect the historic carriage roads.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Park officials estimated the cost of needed infrastructure maintenance to be $65.8 million in 2019, a $6 million increase from 2018.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The National Park Service has an estimated $11 billion in total deferred maintenance across all units, a number which continues to increase.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] The backlog compounds existing problems in environmental management and traffic congestion, as infrastructure to manage traffic flow cannot be built until existing infrastructure is properly maintained.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Trail and wilderness restoration is also deferred due to insufficient funding.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p01] Additionally, the large number of park entrances creates issues with fee compliance, costing additional lost revenue.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The Rockefeller Welcome Center is the only one open throughout the year, though it is closed on winter weekends; the others are all closed in winter.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] After the naval base on the Schoodic Peninsula closed in 2002, the National Park Service (NPS) acquired the land and established the Schoodic Education and Research Center (SERC).
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The SERC campus is managed by the nonprofit Schoodic Institute and the NPS in a public-private partnership as one of 19 NPS research learning centers in the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The center is dedicated to supporting scientific research in the park, providing professional development for teachers, and educating students.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] In 1986, a group of Acadia-area residents and park volunteers formed the membership-based nonprofit organization Friends of Acadia (FOA) to organize volunteer efforts and private philanthropy for the benefit of Acadia National Park.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The group's first major achievement was a $3.4 million endowment, raised between 1991 and 1996, to maintain the park's carriage road system in perpetuity, which leveraged federal funds to fully restore the road system.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] Subsequent projects and partnerships included Acadia Trails Forever, the first endowed trail system in an American national park with $13 million raised between 1999 and 2001, and the Island Explorer, a free, propane-powered bus system serving the park and local communities since 1999.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The Acadia Youth Conservation Corps was established by FOA and endowed by an anonymous donor in 1999 to employ 16 high school students in maintenance of trails and carriage roads in the summer months.
[src:charles-william-eliot/acadia-national-park-p02] The team has since been renamed the Acadia Digital Media Team.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] African-American history began in the 16th century, when mainly West African and Central African slave traders sold African artisans, farmers, and warriors to European slave traders, who transported them across the Atlantic to the Western Hemisphere.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] They were sold as slaves to European colonists and put to work on plantations, particularly in the southern colonies.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] A few were able to achieve freedom through manumission or escape, and founded independent communities before and during the American Revolution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] After the United States was founded in 1783, most American Black people continued to be enslaved, primarily in the American South, with four million enslaved people only liberated after the Northern victory over the South in the Civil War of 1861 to 1865.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] During Reconstruction, African Americans gained citizenship and adult-males the right to vote; however, due to widespread belief in White supremacy, they were treated as second-class citizens and soon effectively disenfranchised in the South.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] These circumstances changed due to participation in the military conflicts of the United States, substantial migration out of the South, the elimination of legal racial segregation, and the civil rights movement which sought political and social freedom.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] However, racism against African Americans and racial socioeconomic disparity remain a problem into the 21st century.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In the 20th and 21st centuries, immigration has played an increasingly significant role in the African-American community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Black population were immigrants, and 20% were either immigrants or the children of immigrants.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] While some Black immigrants or their children may also come to identify as African American, the majority of first-generation immigrants do not, preferring to identify with their nation of origin.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans are of West African and coastal Central African ancestry, with varying amounts of Western European and Native American ancestry (see §Genetics).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] African-American culture has had a significant influence on worldwide culture, making numerous contributions to the English language, literature, politics, cuisine, sports, and music.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The African-American contribution to popular music is so profound that most American popular music, including gospel, blues, jazz, rock and roll, R&B, soul, funk, disco, hip-hop, and house has its origins either partially or entirely in the African-American community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The vast majority of those who were enslaved and transported in the transatlantic slave trade were people from several Central and West African ethnic groups.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] They had been captured directly by European slave traders in coastal raids, or captured and sold by West African slave traders or by half-European "merchant princes" to European slave traders, who brought them to the Americas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The first African slaves in what is now the United States arrived in the early 16th century.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Africans were among Juan Ponce de León's 1513 voyage that landed in what would become Spanish Florida, and enslaved Africans arrived around the same time to Spanish Puerto Rico.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Africans also came via Santo Domingo in the Caribbean to the San Miguel de Gualdape colony (most likely located in the Winyah Bay area of present-day South Carolina), founded by Spanish explorer Lucas Vázquez de Ayllón in 1526.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The ill-fated colony was almost immediately disrupted by a fight over leadership, during which the slaves revolted and fled the colony to seek refuge among local Native Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] De Ayllón and many of the colonists died shortly afterward, due to an epidemic and the colony was abandoned.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The settlers and the slaves who had not escaped returned to the Island of Hispaniola, whence they had come.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The enslaved explorer Esteban arrived in Florida with the Narváez expedition in 1528, a journey that first landed in Santo Domingo and later traveled into Spanish Texas and the Southwest before ending in Mexico.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The marriage between Luisa de Abrego, a free Black domestic servant from Seville, and Miguel Rodríguez, a White Segovian conquistador in 1565 in St.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Augustine (Spanish Florida), is the first known and recorded Christian marriage anywhere in what is now the continental United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The first recorded Africans in English America (including most of the future United States) were "20 and odd negroes" who arrived in Jamestown, Virginia via Cape Comfort in August 1619 as indentured servants.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] As many Virginian settlers began to die from harsh conditions, more and more Africans were brought to work as laborers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] An indentured servant (who could be White or Black) would work for several years (usually four to seven) without wages.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The status of indentured servants in early Virginia and Maryland was similar to slavery.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Servants could be bought, sold, or leased, and they could be physically beaten for disobedience or attempting to running away.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Unlike slaves, they were freed after their term of service expired or if their freedom was purchased.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Their children did not inherit their status, and on their release from contract they received "a year's provision of corn, double apparel, tools necessary", and a small cash payment called "freedom dues".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Africans could legally raise crops and cattle to purchase their freedom.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] They raised families, married other Africans and sometimes intermarried with Native Americans or European settlers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By the 1640s and 1650s, several African families owned farms around Jamestown, and some became wealthy by colonial standards and purchased indentured servants of their own.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1640, the Virginia General Court recorded the earliest documentation of lifetime slavery when they sentenced John Punch, a Negro, to lifetime servitude under his master Hugh Gwyn, for running away.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Florida, some Spanish married or had unions with Pensacola, Creek or African women, both enslaved and free, and their descendants created a mixed-race population of mestizos and mulattos.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The Spanish encouraged slaves from the colony of Georgia to come to Florida as a refuge, promising freedom in exchange for conversion to Catholicism.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] King Charles II issued a royal proclamation freeing all slaves who fled to Spanish Florida and accepted conversion and baptism.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Augustine, but escaped slaves also reached Pensacola.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Augustine had mustered an all-Black militia unit defending Spanish Florida as early as 1683.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] One of the Dutch African arrivals, Anthony Johnson, would later own one of the first Black "slaves", John Casor, resulting from the court ruling of a civil case.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The popular conception of a race-based slave system did not fully develop until the 18th century.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The Dutch West India Company introduced slavery in 1625 with the importation of eleven Black slaves into New Amsterdam (present-day New York City).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] All the colony's slaves, however, were freed upon its surrender to the English.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Massachusetts was the first English colony to legally recognize slavery in 1641.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1662, Virginia passed a law that children of enslaved women would take the status of the mother, rather than that of the father, as was the case under common law.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] This legal principle was called *partus sequitur ventrum*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By an act of 1699, Virginia ordered the deportation of all free Blacks, effectively defining all people of African descent who remained in the colony as slaves.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1670, the colonial assembly passed a law prohibiting free and baptized Blacks (and Native Americans) from purchasing Christians (in this act meaning White Europeans) but allowing them to buy people "of their owne nation".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In Spanish Louisiana, although there was no movement toward abolition of the African slave trade, Spanish rule introduced a new law called *coartación*, which allowed slaves to buy their freedom, and that of others.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Although some did not have the money to do so, government measures on slavery enabled the existence of many free Blacks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] This caused problems to the Spaniards with the French creoles (French who had settled in New France) who had also populated Spanish Louisiana.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The French creoles cited that measure as one of the system's worst elements.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] First established in South Carolina in 1704, groups of armed White men—slave patrols—were formed to monitor enslaved Black people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Their function was to police slaves, especially fugitives.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Slave owners feared that slaves might organize revolts or slave rebellions, so state militias were formed to provide a military command structure and discipline within the slave patrols.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] These patrols were used to detect, encounter, and crush any organized slave meetings which might lead to revolts or rebellions.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The earliest African American congregations and churches were organized before 1800 in both northern and southern cities following the Great Awakening.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By 1775, Africans made up 20% of the population in the American colonies, which made them the second-largest ethnic group after English Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] During the 1770s, Africans, both enslaved and free, helped rebellious American colonists secure their independence by defeating the British in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Blacks played a role in both sides in the American Revolution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Activists in the Patriot cause included James Armistead, Prince Whipple, and Oliver Cromwell.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Around 15,000 Black Loyalists left with the British after the war, most of them ending up as free Black people in England or its colonies, such as the Black Nova Scotians and the Sierra Leone Creole people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In the Spanish Louisiana, Governor Bernardo de Gálvez organized Spanish free Black men into two militia companies to defend New Orleans during the American Revolution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] They fought in the 1779 battle in which Spain captured Baton Rouge from the British.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Gálvez also commanded them in campaigns against the British outposts in Mobile, Alabama, and Pensacola, Florida.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] He recruited slaves for the militia by pledging to free anyone who was seriously wounded and promised to secure a low price for *coartación* (buy their freedom and that of others) for those who received lesser wounds.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] During the 1790s, Governor Francisco Luis Héctor, baron of Carondelet reinforced local fortifications and recruit even more free Black men for the militia.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Carondelet doubled the number of free Black men who served, creating two more militia companies—one made up of Black members and the other of pardo (mixed race).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Serving in the militia brought free Black men one step closer to equality with Whites, allowing them, for example, the right to carry arms and boosting their earning power.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] However, actually these privileges distanced free Black men from enslaved Blacks and encouraged them to identify with Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Slavery had been tacitly enshrined in the US Constitution through provisions such as Article I, Section 2, Clause 3, commonly known as the 3/5 compromise.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Due to the restrictions of Section 9, Clause 1, Congress was unable to pass an Act Prohibiting Importation of Slaves until 1807.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Fugitive slave laws (derived from the Fugitive Slave Clause of the Constitution—Article IV, Section 2, Clause 3) were passed by Congress in both 1793 and 1850, guaranteeing the right of a slaveholder to recover an escaped slave anywhere within the US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Slave owners, who viewed enslaved people as property, ensured that it became a federal crime to aid or assist those who had fled slavery or to interfere with their capture.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By that time, slavery, which almost exclusively targeted Black people, had become the most critical and contentious political issue in the Antebellum United States, repeatedly sparking crises and conflicts.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Among these were the Missouri Compromise, the Compromise of 1850, the infamous Dred Scott decision, and John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Prior to the Civil War, eight serving presidents had owned slaves, a practice that was legally protected under the US Constitution.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By 1860, the number of enslaved Black people in the US had grown to between 3.5 and 4.4 million, largely as a result of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In addition, 488,000–500,000 Black people lived free around the country, with legislated limits imposed upon them in addition to "unconquerable prejudice" from Whites according to Henry Clay.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In response to these conditions, some free Black people chose to leave the US and emigrate to Liberia in West Africa.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Liberia had been established in 1821 as a settlement by the American Colonization Society (ACS), with many abolitionist members of the ACS believing Black Americans would have greater opportunities for freedom and equality in Africa than they would in the US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Slaves not only represented a significant financial investment for their owners, but they also played a crucial role in producing the country's most valuable product and export: cotton.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Enslaved people were instrumental in the construction of several prominent structures such as, the United States Capitol, the White House and other Washington, D.C.–based buildings.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Similar building projects existed in the slave states.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By 1815, the domestic slave trade had become a significant and major economic activity in the United States, continuing to flourish until the 1860s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Historians estimate that nearly one million individuals were subjected to this forced migration, which was often referred to as a new "Middle Passage".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The historian Ira Berlin described this internal forced migration of enslaved people as the "central event" in the life of a slave during the period between the American Revolution and the Civil War.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Berlin emphasized that whether enslaved individuals were directly uprooted or lived in constant fear that they or their families would be involuntarily relocated, "the massive deportation traumatized Black people" throughout the US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] As a result of this large-scale forced movement, countless individuals lost their connection to families and clans, and many ethnic Africans lost their knowledge of varying tribal origins in Africa.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Emigration of free Blacks to their continent of origin had been proposed since the Revolutionary war.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] After Haiti became independent, it tried to recruit African Americans to migrate there after it re-established trade relations with the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The Haitian Union was a group formed to promote relations between the countries.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] After riots against Blacks in Cincinnati, its Black community sponsored founding of the Wilberforce Colony, an initially successful settlement of African American immigrants to Canada.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The colony was one of the first such independent political entities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] It lasted for a number of decades and provided a destination for about 200 Black families emigrating from a number of locations in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1863, during the American Civil War, President Abraham Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The proclamation declared that all slaves in Confederate-held territory were free.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Advancing Union troops enforced the proclamation, with Texas being the last state to be emancipated, in 1865.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Slavery in a few border states continued until the ratification of the Thirteenth Amendment in December 1865.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] While the Naturalization Act of 1790 limited US citizenship to Whites only, the 14th Amendment (1868) gave Black people citizenship, and the 15th Amendment (1870) gave Black men the right to vote.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] African Americans quickly set up congregations for themselves, as well as schools and community/civic associations, to have space away from White control or oversight.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] While the post-war Reconstruction era was initially a time of progress for African Americans, that period ended in 1876.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By the late 1890s, Southern states enacted Jim Crow laws to enforce racial segregation and disenfranchisement.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Segregation was now imposed with Jim Crow laws, using signs used to show Blacks where they could legally walk, talk, drink, rest, or eat.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] For those places that were racially mixed, non-Whites had to wait until all White customers were dealt with.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Most African Americans obeyed the Jim Crow laws, to avoid racially motivated violence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] To maintain self-esteem and dignity, African Americans such as Anthony Overton and Mary McLeod Bethune continued to build their own schools, churches, banks, social clubs, and other businesses.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In the last decade of the 19th century, racially discriminatory laws and racial violence aimed at African Americans began to mushroom in the United States, a period often referred to as the "nadir of American race relations".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] These discriminatory acts included racial segregation—upheld by the United States Supreme Court decision in *Plessy v.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The desperate conditions of African Americans in the South sparked the Great Migration during the first half of the 20th century which led to a growing African American community in Northern and Western United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The rapid influx of Blacks disturbed the racial balance within Northern and Western cities, exacerbating hostility between both Blacks and Whites in the two regions.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The Red Summer of 1919 was marked by hundreds of deaths and higher casualties across the US as a result of race riots that occurred in more than three dozen cities, such as the Chicago race riot of 1919 and the Omaha race riot of 1919.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Overall, Blacks in Northern and Western cities experienced systemic discrimination in a plethora of aspects of life.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Within employment, economic opportunities for Blacks were routed to the lowest-status and restrictive in potential mobility.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] While many Whites defended their space with violence, intimidation, or legal tactics toward African Americans, many other Whites migrated to more racially homogeneous suburban or exurban regions, a process known as White flight.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Despite discrimination, drawing cards for leaving the hopelessness in the South were the growth of African American institutions and communities in Northern cities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Institutions included Black oriented organizations (e.g., Urban League, NAACP), churches, businesses, and newspapers, as well as successes in the development in African American intellectual culture, music, and popular culture (e.g., Harlem Renaissance, Chicago Black Renaissance).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The Cotton Club in Harlem was a Whites-only establishment, with Blacks (such as Duke Ellington) allowed to perform, but to a White audience.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Black Americans also found a new ground for political power in Northern cities, without the enforced disabilities of Jim Crow.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By the 1950s, the civil rights movement was gaining momentum.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] A 1955 lynching that sparked public outrage about injustice was that of Emmett Till, a 14-year-old boy from Chicago.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Spending the summer with relatives in Money, Mississippi, Till was killed for allegedly having wolf-whistled at a White woman.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Till had been badly beaten, one of his eyes was gouged out, and he was shot in the head.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The visceral response to his mother's decision to have an open-casket funeral mobilized the Black community throughout the US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Vann Newkirk wrote "the trial of his killers became a pageant illuminating the tyranny of White supremacy".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The state of Mississippi tried two defendants, but they were speedily acquitted by an all-White jury.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom and the conditions which brought it into being are credited with putting pressure on presidents John F.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] By 1966, the emergence of the Black Power movement, which lasted from 1966 to 1975, expanded upon the aims of the civil rights movement to include economic and political self-sufficiency, and freedom from White authority.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] During the post-war period, many African Americans continued to be economically disadvantaged relative to other Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Average Black income stood at 54 percent of that of White workers in 1947, and 55 percent in 1962.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 43 percent of all Black families fell into the poverty bracket, earning under $3,000 (equivalent to $30,649 in 2025) a year.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] The 1960s saw improvements in the social and economic conditions of many Black Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] From 1965 to 1969, Black family income rose from 54 to 60 percent of White family income.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1968, 23 percent of Black families earned under $3,000 (equivalent to $27,775 in 2025) a year, compared with 41 percent in 1960.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1965, 19 percent of Black Americans had incomes equal to the national median, a proportion that rose to 27 percent by 1967.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1960, the median level of education for Blacks had been 10.8 years, and by the late 1960s, the figure rose to 12.2 years, half a year behind the median for Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Politically and economically, African Americans have made substantial strides during the post–civil rights era.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1967, Thurgood Marshall became the first African American Supreme Court Justice.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1968, Shirley Chisholm became the first Black woman elected to the US Congress.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1989, Douglas Wilder became the first African American elected governor in US history.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Clarence Thomas succeeded Marshall to become the second African American Supreme Court Justice in 1991.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 1992, Carol Moseley-Braun of Illinois became the first African American woman elected to the US Senate.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] There were 8,936 Black officeholders in the United States in 2000, showing a net increase of 7,467 since 1970.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 2005, the number of Africans immigrating to the United States, in a single year, surpassed the peak number who were involuntarily brought to the United States during the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] On November 4, 2008, Democratic Senator Barack Obama—the son of a White American mother and a Kenyan father—defeated Republican Senator John McCain to become the first African American to be elected president.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] At least 95 percent of African American voters voted for Obama.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] He also received overwhelming support from young and educated Whites, a majority of Asians, and Hispanics, picking up a number of new states in the Democratic electoral column.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Obama lost the overall White vote, although he won a larger proportion of White votes than any previous non-incumbent Democratic presidential candidate since Jimmy Carter.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] Obama was reelected for a second and final term, by a similar margin on November 6, 2012.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In 2021, Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican father and Indian mother, became the first woman, the first African American, and the first Asian American to serve as Vice President of the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p01] In June 2021, Juneteenth, a day which commemorates the end of slavery in the US, became a federal holiday.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1790, when the first US census was taken, Africans (including slaves and free people) numbered about 760,000—about 19.3% of the population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1860, at the start of the Civil War, the African American population had increased to 4.4 million, but the percentage rate dropped to 14% of the overall population of the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The vast majority were slaves, with only 488,000 counted as "freemen".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1900, the Black population had doubled and reached 8.8 million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1910, about 90% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Large numbers began migrating north looking for better job opportunities and living conditions, and to escape Jim Crow laws and racial violence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The Great Migration, as it was called, spanned the 1890s to the 1970s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] From 1916 through the 1960s, more than six million Black people moved north.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] But in the 1970s and 1980s, that trend reversed, with more African Americans moving south to the Sun Belt than leaving it.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1990, the African American population reached about 30 million and represented 12% of the US population, roughly the same proportion as in 1900.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] At the time of the 2000 US census, 54.8% of African Americans lived in the South.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In that year, 17.6% of African Americans lived in the Northeast and 18.7% in the Midwest, while only 8.9% lived in the Western states.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The west does have a sizable Black population in certain areas, however.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] California, the nation's most populous state, has the fifth-largest African American population, only behind New York, Texas, Georgia, and Florida.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to the 2000 census, approximately 2.05% of African Americans identified as Hispanic or Latino in origin, many of whom may be of Brazilian, Puerto Rican, Dominican, Cuban, Haitian, or other Latin American descent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The only self-reported *ancestral* groups larger than African Americans are the Irish and Germans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to the 2010 census, nearly 3% of people who self-identified as Black had recent ancestors who immigrated from another country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Self-reported non-Hispanic Black immigrants from the Caribbean, mostly from Jamaica and Haiti, represented 0.9% of the US population, at 2.6 million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants from sub-Saharan Africa also represented 0.9%, at about 2.8 million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Additionally, self-identified Black Hispanics represented 0.4% of the United States population, at about 1.2 million people, largely found within the Puerto Rican and Dominican communities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Self-reported Black immigrants hailing from other countries in the Americas, such as Brazil and Canada, as well as several European countries, represented less than 0.1% of the population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Mixed-race Hispanic and non-Hispanic Americans who identified as being part Black, represented 0.9% of the population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Of the 12.6% of United States residents who identified as Black, around 10.3% were "native Black American" or ethnic African Americans, who are direct descendants of West/Central Africans brought to the US as slaves.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] These individuals make up well over 80% of all Blacks in the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] When including people of mixed-race origin, about 13.5% of the US population self-identified as Black or "mixed with Black".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] However, according to the US Census Bureau, evidence from the 2000 census indicates that many African and Caribbean immigrant ethnic groups do not identify as "Black, African Am., or Negro".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Instead, they wrote in their own respective ethnic groups in the "Some Other Race" write-in entry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] As a result, the census bureau devised a new, separate "African American" ethnic group category in 2010 for ethnic African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Nigerian Americans and Ethiopian Americans were the most reported sub-Saharan African groups in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the 2020 census, the African American population was undercounted at an estimated rate of 3.3%, up from 2.1% in 2010.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Texas has the largest African American population by state with approximately four million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Followed by Texas is Florida, with 3.8 million, and Georgia, with 3.6 million.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Mississippi is the state with the highest African American share of the population at 39%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Followed by Mississippi is Louisiana at 34%, and Georgia at 32%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] After 100 years of African Americans leaving the south in large numbers seeking better opportunities and treatment in the west and north, a movement known as the Great Migration, there is now a reverse trend, called the New Great Migration.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] As with the earlier Great Migration, the New Great Migration is primarily directed toward cities and large urban areas, such as Charlotte, Houston, Dallas, Fort Worth, Huntsville, Raleigh, Tampa, San Antonio, New Orleans, Memphis, Nashville, Jacksonville, and so forth.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] A growing percentage of African Americans from the west and north are migrating to the southern region of the US for economic and cultural reasons.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2020, New York City, Chicago, and Los Angeles metropolitan areas had the highest decline in African Americans, while Atlanta, Dallas, and Houston had the highest increase respectively.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Despite recent declines, as of 2020, the New York City metropolitan area still has the largest African American metropolitan population in the United States and the only to have over three million African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Among cities of 100,000 or more, South Fulton, Georgia had the highest percentage of Black residents of any large US city in 2020, with 93%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Claiborne County, Mississippi is the Blackest county in the U.S. at 87% Black in 2020.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Cook County, Illinois has the largest Black population in the U.S. with 1,185,601 Black residents in 2020.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The nation's most affluent community with an African American majority resides in View Park–Windsor Hills, California, with an annual median household income of $159,618 and median home price of about $1.5 million in 2025.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Additionally, there is a significant affluent Black presence in the southern Chicago suburbs of Cook County, Illinois.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2006, Queens County, New York was the only county with a population of 65,000 or more where African Americans had a higher median household income than White Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Seatack, Virginia is currently the oldest African American community in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] It survives today with a vibrant and active civic community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] During slavery, anti-literacy laws were enacted in the US that prohibited education for Black people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Slave owners saw literacy as a threat to the institution of slavery.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] When slavery was finally abolished in 1865, public educational systems were expanding across the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1870, around seventy-four institutions in the south provided a form of advanced education for African American students.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1900, over a hundred programs at these schools provided training for Black professionals, including teachers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Many of the students at Fisk University, including the young W.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Du Bois, taught school during the summers to support their studies.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans were very concerned to provide quality education for their children, but White supremacy limited their ability to participate in educational policymaking on the political level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] State governments soon moved to undermine their citizenship by restricting their right to vote.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By the late 1870s, Blacks were disenfranchised and segregated across the American South.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] White politicians in Mississippi and other states withheld financial resources and supplies from Black schools.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Nevertheless, the presence of Black teachers, and their engagement with their communities both inside and outside the classroom, ensured that Black students had access to education despite these external constraints.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] During World War II, demands for unity and racial tolerance on the home front provided an opening for the first Black history curriculum in the country.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] For example, during the early 1940s, Madeline Morgan, a Black teacher in the Chicago public schools, created a curriculum for students in grades one through eight highlighting the contributions of Black people to the history of the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] At the close of the war, Chicago's Board of Education downgraded the curriculum's status from mandatory to optional.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Predominantly Black schools for kindergarten through twelfth grade students were common throughout the US before the 1970s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1972, however, desegregation efforts meant that only 25% of Black students were in schools with more than 90% non-White students.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] However, since then, a trend towards re-segregation affected communities across the country: by 2011, 2.9 million African American students were in such overwhelmingly minority schools, including 53% of Black students in school districts that were formerly under desegregation orders.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] As late as 1947, about one third of African Americans over 65 were considered to lack the literacy to read and write their own names.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By 1969, illiteracy as it had been traditionally defined, had been largely eradicated among younger African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Between 1995 and 2009, freshmen college enrollment for African Americans increased by 73 percent and only 15 percent for Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black women are enrolled in college more than any other race and gender group, leading all with 9.7% enrolled according to the 2011 US census.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The average high school graduation rate of Blacks in the United States has steadily increased to 71% in 2013.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Separating this statistic into component parts shows it varies greatly depending upon the state and the school district examined.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] 38% of Black males graduated in the state of New York but in Maine 97% graduated and exceeded the White male graduation rate by 11 percentage points.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In much of the southeastern United States and some parts of the southwestern United States the graduation rate of White males was in fact below 70% such as in Florida where 62% of White males graduated from high school.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Examining specific school districts paints an even more complex picture.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the Detroit school district, the graduation rate of Black males was 20% but 7% for White males.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the New York City school district 28% of Black males graduate from high school compared to 57% of White males.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In Newark County 76% of Black males graduated compared to 67% for White males.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Further academic improvement has occurred in 2015.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Roughly 23% of all Blacks have bachelor's degrees.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1988, 21% of Whites had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 11% of Blacks.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2015, 23% of Blacks had obtained a bachelor's degree versus 36% of Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Foreign born Blacks, 9% of the Black population, made even greater strides.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] They exceed native born Blacks by 10 percentage points.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] College Board, which runs the official college-level advanced placement (AP) programs in American high schools, have has received criticism in recent years that its curricula have focused too much on Euro-centric history.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2020, College Board reshaped some curricula among history-based courses to further reflect the African diaspora.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2021, College Board announced it would be piloting an AP African American Studies course between 2022 and 2024.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The course officially launched in August 2024.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In June 2023, the Supreme Court ended race-based affirmative action at American colleges and universities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In response, many of the nation's most prominent historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs) have reported a significant surge in applications and enrollment.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Slightly more than 250,000 African American students in the high school graduating class of 2025 took the Scholastic Aptitude Test (SAT) making up 13% of test takers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American students had an average score of 904 which is lower than the national average of 1,209.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Asian American students had the highest average with 1,229.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to a 2025 study, African Americans have the highest average student debt.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans with bachelor's degrees owe an average of $52,726 in student loans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Nearly 70% of African Americans took out a loan to fund their undergraduate education.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American women, in particular, carry the highest average student debt in the nation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Historically black colleges and universities (HBCUs), which were founded when segregated institutions of higher learning did not admit African Americans, continue to thrive and educate students of all races today.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] There are 107 HBCUs representing three percent of the nation's colleges and universities with the majority established in the Southeast.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] HBCUs have been largely responsible for establishing and expanding the African American middle-class by providing more career opportunities for African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The economic disparity between the races in the US has marginally improved since the end of slavery.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1863, two years prior to emancipation, Black people owned 0.5 percent of the national wealth, while in 2019 it is just over 1.5 percent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Racial disparity in poverty rates has narrowed since the civil rights era, with the poverty rate among African Americans decreasing from 24.7% in 2004 to 18.8% in 2020, compared to 10.5% for all Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Poverty is associated with higher rates of marital stress and dissolution, physical and mental health problems, disability, cognitive deficits, low educational attainment, and crime.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans have a long and diverse history of business ownership.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Although the first African American business is unknown, slaves captured from West Africa are believed to have established commercial enterprises as peddlers and skilled craftspeople as far back as the 17th century.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Washington became the most famous proponent of African American businesses.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] DuBois also commended business as a vehicle for African American advancement.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2002, African American-owned businesses accounted for 1.2 million of the US's 23 million businesses.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] As of 2011, African American-owned businesses account for approximately two million US businesses.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black-owned businesses experienced the largest growth in number of businesses among minorities from 2002 to 2011.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Twenty-five percent of Blacks had white-collar occupations (management, professional, and related fields) in 2000, compared with 33.6% of Americans overall.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2001, over half of African American households of married couples earned $50,000 or more.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Although in the same year African Americans were over-represented among the nation's poor, this was directly related to the disproportionate percentage of African American families headed by single women; such families are collectively poorer, regardless of ethnicity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2006, the median earnings of African American men was more than Black and non-Black American women overall, and in all educational levels.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] At the same time, among American men, income disparities were significant; the median income of African American men was approximately 76 cents for every dollar of their European American counterparts, although the gap narrowed somewhat with a rise in educational level.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Overall, the median earnings of African American men were 72 cents for every dollar earned of their Asian American counterparts, and $1.17 for every dollar earned by Hispanic men.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, by 2006, among American women with post-secondary education, African American women have made significant advances; the median income of African American women was more than those of their Asian-, European- and Hispanic American counterparts with at least some college education.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The US public sector is the single most important source of employment for African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] During 2008–2010, 21.2% of all Black workers were public employees, compared with 16.3% of non-Black workers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Both before and after the onset of the Great Recession, African Americans were 30% more likely than other workers to be employed in the public sector.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The public sector is also a critical source of decent-paying jobs for Black Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] For both men and women, the median wage earned by Black employees is significantly higher in the public sector than in other industries.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1999, the median income of African American families was $33,255 compared to $53,356 of European Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In times of economic hardship for the nation, African Americans suffer disproportionately from job loss and underemployment, with the Black underclass being hardest hit.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The phrase "last hired and first fired" is reflected in the Bureau of Labor Statistics unemployment figures.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Nationwide, the October 2008 unemployment rate for African Americans was 11.1%, while the nationwide rate was 6.5%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2007, the average income for African Americans was approximately $34,000, compared to $55,000 for Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans experience a higher rate of unemployment than the general population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The income gap between Black and White families is also significant.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2005, employed Blacks earned 65% of the wages of Whites, down from 82% in 1975.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] *The New York Times* reported in 2006 that in Queens, New York, the median income among African American families exceeded that of White families, which the newspaper attributed to the growth in the number of two-parent Black families.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] It noted that Queens was the only county with more than 65,000 residents where that was true.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2011, it was reported that 72% of Black babies were born to unwed mothers.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The poverty rate among single-parent Black families was 39.5% in 2005, according to Walter E.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Williams, while it was 9.9% among married-couple Black families.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Among White families, the respective rates were 26.4% and 6% in poverty.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Collectively, African Americans are more involved in the American political process than other minority groups in the United States, indicated by the highest level of voter registration and participation in elections among these groups in 2004.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have the highest level of Congressional representation of any minority group in the US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Homeownership in the US is the strongest indicator of financial stability and the primary asset most Americans use to generate wealth.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans continue to lag behind other racial groups in homeownership.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the first quarter of 2021, 45.1% of African Americans owned their homes, compared to 65.3% of all Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate has remained relatively flat since the 1970s despite an increase in anti-discrimination housing laws and protections.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The African American homeownership rate peaked in 2004 at 49.7%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The average White high school drop-out still has a slightly better chance of owning a home than the average African American college graduate usually due to unfavorable debt-to-income ratios or credit scores among most African American college graduates.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Since 2000, fast-growing housing costs in most cities have made it even more difficult for the US African American homeownership rate to significantly grow and reach over 50% for the first time in history.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] From 2000 to 2022, the median home price in the US grew 160%, outpacing average annual household income growth in that same period, which only grew about 30%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] South Carolina is the state with the most African American homeownership, with about 55% of African Americans owning their own homes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black people, who make up 12% of the total U.S. population, make up 32% of all people experiencing homelessness, according to the data.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Since the mid 20th century, a large majority of African Americans support the Democratic Party.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 Presidential election, 86% of African American voters supported Democrat Kamala Harris, while 13% supported Republican Donald Trump.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Although there is an African American lobby in foreign policy, it has not had the impact that African American organizations have had in domestic policy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Many African Americans were excluded from electoral politics in the decades following the end of Reconstruction.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The African American trend of voting for Democrats can be traced back to the 1930s during the Great Depression, when Franklin D.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal program provided economic relief to African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Roosevelt's New Deal coalition turned the Democratic Party into an organization of the working class and their liberal allies, regardless of region.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The African American vote became even more solidly Democratic when Democratic presidents John F.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Johnson pushed for civil rights legislation during the 1960s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1960, nearly a third of African Americans voted for Republican Richard Nixon.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Conservatism has been growing among African Americans, particularly since the 2020 Presidential election.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the 2024 election, Trump secured a slightly larger share of the African American vote compared to his 2020 performance.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] "Lift Every Voice and Sing" is often referred to as the Black national anthem in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) had dubbed it the "Negro national anthem" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The majority of African Americans are Protestant, many of whom follow the historically Black churches.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The term Black church refers to churches which minister to predominantly African American congregations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black congregations were first established by freed slaves at the end of the 17th century, and later when slavery was abolished more African Americans were allowed to create a unique form of Christianity that was culturally influenced by African spiritual traditions.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to a 2007 survey, more than half of the African American population are part of the historically Black churches.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The largest Protestant denomination among African Americans is the Baptists, distributed mainly in four denominations, the largest being the National Baptist Convention, USA and the National Baptist Convention of America.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The second-largest is the Methodists, the largest organizations of which are the African Methodist Episcopal Church and the African Methodist Episcopal Zion Church.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Pentecostals are distributed among several different religious bodies, with the Church of God in Christ as the largest among them by far.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] About 16% of African American Christians are members of White Protestant communions; these denominations (which include the United Church of Christ) mostly have a 2–3% African American membership.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] There are also large numbers of Catholics, constituting 5% of the African American population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Of the total number of Jehovah's Witnesses, 22% are Black.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Historically, between 15 and 30% of enslaved Africans brought to the Americas were Muslims, but most of these Africans were converted to Christianity during the era of American slavery.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Prominent members included activist Malcolm X and boxer Muhammad Ali.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Malcolm X is considered the first person to start the movement among African Americans towards mainstream Islam, after he left the Nation and made the pilgrimage to Mecca.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1975, Warith Deen Mohammed, the son of Elijah Muhammad took control of the Nation after his father's death and guided the majority of its members to orthodox Islam.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American Muslims constitute 20% of the total US Muslim population, the majority are Sunni or orthodox Muslims, some of these identify under the community of W.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The Nation of Islam led by Louis Farrakhan has a membership ranging from 20,000 to 50,000 members.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] There is also a small but growing group of African American Jews, making up less than 0.5% of African Americans or about 2% of the Jewish population in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The majority of African-American Jews are Ashkenazi, while smaller numbers identify as Sephardi, Mizrahi, or other.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Many African-American Jews are affiliated with denominations such as the Reform, Conservative, Reconstructionist, or Orthodox branches of Judaism, but the majority identify as "Jews of no religion", commonly known as secular Jews.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] A significant number of people who identify themselves as "Black Jews" are affiliated with syncretic religious groups, largely the Black Hebrew Israelites, whose beliefs include the claim that African Americans are descended from the Biblical Israelites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Jews of all races typically do not accept Black Hebrew Israelites as Jews, in part because they are usually not Jewish according to Jewish law, and in part because these groups are sometimes associated with antisemitism.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African-American Jews have criticized the Black Hebrew Israelites, regarding the movement as primarily composed of Black non-Jews who have appropriated Black-Jewish identity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the 2010s, confirmed atheists were less than one half of one percent, similar to numbers for Hispanics.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2025, a Pew Research Center study found that, among Black Americans, Christian affiliation has declined in recent years.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The share of Black adults identifying as Christian fell from 85% in 2007 to 79% in 2014 and 73% in 2021, mirroring a broader decline in Christianity in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] However, Black adults remain more likely than U.S. adults overall to identify as Christian (73% vs.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] By comparison, about half or fewer adults in other racial or ethnic groups report that religion is very important or that they pray daily, and even smaller shares attend services monthly.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Religiosity among Black Americans also varies by age.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] 39% of Black adults aged 65 and older describe themselves as very religious, compared with 21% of those under 30.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] This age pattern is similar to that observed among White and Hispanic Americans, although Black adults of all ages are more likely than other groups to describe themselves as very religious.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to a Gallup survey, 4.6% of Black or African Americans self-identified as LGBT in 2016, while the total portion of American adults in all ethnic groups identifying as LGBT was 4.1% in 2016.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American women are more likely than African American men to openly identify as LGBT.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The life expectancy for Black men in 2008 was 70.8 years.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Life expectancy for Black women was 77.5 years in 2008.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1900, when information on Black life expectancy started being collated, a Black man could expect to live to 32.5 years and a Black woman 33.5 years.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 1900, White men lived an average of 46.3 years and White women lived an average of 48.3 years.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American life expectancy at birth is persistently five to seven years lower than European Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black men have shorter lifespans than any other group in the US besides Native American men.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black people have higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and hypertension than the US average.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] For adult Black men, the rate of obesity was 31.6% in 2010.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] For adult Black women, the rate of obesity was 41.2% in 2010.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans have higher rates of mortality than any other racial or ethnic group for eight of the top ten causes of death.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2013, among men, Black men had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by White, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander (A/PI), and American Indian/Alaska Native (AI/AN) men.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Among women, White women had the highest rate of getting cancer, followed by Black, Hispanic, Asian/Pacific Islander, and American Indian/Alaska Native women.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans also have higher prevalence and incidence of Alzheimer's disease compared to the overall average.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black women lead the nation in abortions.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to a 2022 report, Black women made up 40% of abortions despite making up 13% of the U.S. woman population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans are more likely than White Americans to die due to health-related problems developed by alcoholism.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Alcohol abuse is the main contributor to the top three causes of death among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In December 2020, African Americans were less likely to be vaccinated against COVID-19 due to mistrust in the US medical system.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] From 2021 to 2022, there was an increase in African Americans who became vaccinated.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Still, in 2022, COVID-19 complications became the third leading cause of death for African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Violence is a major problem within the African American community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] A report from the US Department of Justice states "In 2005, homicide victimization rates for Blacks were more than six times as high as the rates for Whites".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The report also found that "94% of Black victims were killed by Blacks." Of the nearly 20,000 recorded US homicides in 2022, African Americans made up the majority of offenders and victims despite making up less than 15% of the population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2024, all of the five most dangerous US cities have a significant Black population and highly concerning Black-on-Black violent crime rate.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black males age 15–44 are the only race/sex category for which homicide is a top-five cause of death.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black women are three times more likely to be killed by an intimate partner than White women.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Black children are more than three times as likely to die due to parental abuse and neglect than White children.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, African Americans have higher rates of sexually transmitted infections (STIs) compared to Whites, with five times the rates of syphilis and chlamydia, and 7.5 times the rate of gonorrhea.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The disproportionately high incidence of HIV/AIDS among African Americans has been attributed to homophobic influences, lack of condom usage, and lack of proper healthcare.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black men is seven times higher than the prevalence for White men, and Black men are more than nine times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White men.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The prevalence of HIV/AIDS among Black women is 20 times higher than White women, and Black women are more than 15 times as likely to die from HIV/AIDS-related illness than White women.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans have several barriers for accessing mental health services.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Counseling has been frowned upon and distant in utility and proximity to many people in the African American community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2004, a qualitative research study explored the disconnect with African Americans and mental health.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The study was conducted as a semi-structured discussion which allowed the focus group to express their opinions and life experiences.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] The results revealed a couple key variables that create barriers for many African American communities to seek mental health services such as the stigma, lack of four important necessities; trust, affordability, cultural understanding and impersonal services.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Historically, many African American communities did not seek counseling because religion was a part of the family values.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African Americans who have a faith background are more likely to seek prayer as a coping mechanism for mental issues rather than seeking professional mental health services.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2015 a study concluded, African Americans with high value in religion are less likely to utilize mental health services compared to those who have low value in religion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In the United States, counseling approaches are based on the experience of White Americans and do not fit within the African American culture.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] African American families tend to resolve concerns within the family, and it is viewed by the family as a strength.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] On the other hand, when African Americans seek counseling, they face a social backlash and are criticized.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] They may be labeled "crazy", viewed as weak, and their pride is diminished.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Because of this, many African Americans instead seek mentorship within communities they trust.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Terminology is another barrier in relation to African Americans and mental health.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] There is more stigma on the term *psychotherapy* versus counseling.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In one study, psychotherapy is associated with mental illness whereas counseling approaches problem-solving, guidance and help.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] More African Americans seek assistance when it is called counseling and not psychotherapy because it is more welcoming within the culture and community.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Counselors are encouraged to be aware of such barriers for the well-being of African American clients.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] Without cultural competency training in health care, many African Americans go unheard and misunderstood.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] In 2021, African Americans had the third highest suicide rate trailing American Indians/Alaska Natives and White Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] However, African Americans had the second highest increase of its suicide rate from 2011 to 2021, growing 58%.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p02] As of 2024, suicide is the second leading cause of death among African-Americans between the ages of 15 and 24, with Black men being four times more likely to kill themselves than Black women.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Recent studies of African Americans using genetic testing have found ancestry to vary by region and sex of ancestors.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] These studies found that on average, African Americans have 73.2–82.1% Sub-Saharan African, 16.7–24% European, and 0.8–1.2% Native American genetic ancestry, with large variation between individuals.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Commercial testing services have reported similar variation, with ranges from 0.6 to 2 percent Native American, 19 to 29 percent European, and 65 to 80 percent Sub-Saharan African ancestry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to a genome-wide study by Bryc et al.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2009), the mixed ancestry of African Americans in varying ratios came about as the result of sexual contact between West/Central Africans (more frequently females) and Europeans (more frequently males).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This can be understood as being the result of enslaved African American females being raped by White males.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Consequently, the 365 African Americans in their sample have a genome-wide average of 78.1% West African ancestry and 18.5% European ancestry, with large variation among individuals (ranging from 99% to 1% West African ancestry).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The West African ancestral component in African Americans is most similar to that in present-day speakers from the non-Bantu branches of the Niger-Congo family.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2014) observed that around 50% of the overall ancestry of African Americans traces comes from a population similar to the Niger-Congo-speaking Yoruba of southern Nigeria and southern Benin, reflecting the centrality of this West African region in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent ancestral component found among African Americans was derived from Great Britain, in keeping with historical records.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] It constitutes a little over 10% of their overall ancestry and is most similar to the Northwest European ancestral component also carried by Barbadians.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2009) found a similar proportion of Yoruba-like ancestry in their African American samples, with a minority also drawn from Mandenka and Bantu populations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Additionally, the researchers observed an average European ancestry of 21.9%, again with significant variation between individuals.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2009) note that populations from other parts of the continent may also constitute adequate proxies for the ancestors of some African American individuals; namely, ancestral populations from Guinea Bissau, Senegal and Sierra Leone in West Africa and Angola in Southern Africa.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] An individual African American person can have over fifteen African ethnic groups in their genetic makeup alone due to the slave trade covering such vast areas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Altogether, genetic studies suggest that African Americans are a genetically diverse people.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to DNA analysis led in 2006 by Penn State geneticist Mark D.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to Shriver, around five percent of African Americans also have at least 12.5% Native American ancestry (equivalent to one Native American great-grandparent and their forebears).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Research suggests that Native American ancestry among people who identify as African American is a result of relationships that occurred soon after slave ships arrived in the American colonies, and European ancestry is of more recent origin, often from the decades before the Civil War.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Africans bearing the E-V38 (E1b1a) likely traversed across the Sahara, from east to west, approximately 19,000 years ago.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] E-M2 (E1b1a1) likely originated in West Africa or Central Africa.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to a Y-DNA study by Sims et al.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2007), the majority (≈60%) of African Americans belong to various subclades of the E-M2 (E1b1a1, formerly E3a) paternal haplogroup.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This is the most common genetic paternal lineage found today among West/Central African males and is also a signature of the historical Bantu migrations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The next most frequent Y-DNA haplogroup observed among African Americans is the R1b clade, which around 15% of African Americans carry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This lineage is most common today among Northwestern European males.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The remaining African Americans mainly belong to the paternal haplogroup I (≈7%), which is also frequent in Northwestern Europe.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to an mtDNA study by Salas et al.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] (2005), the maternal lineages of African Americans are most similar to haplogroups that are today especially common in West Africa (>55%), followed closely by West-Central Africa and Southwestern Africa (<41%).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The characteristic West African haplogroups L1b, L2b,c,d, and L3b,d and West-Central African haplogroups L1c and L3e in particular occur at high frequencies among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As with the paternal DNA of African Americans, contributions from other parts of the continent to their maternal gene pool are insignificant.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Formal political, economic and social discrimination against minorities has been present throughout American history.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Saito, Associate Professor of Sociology and American Studies & Ethnicity at the University of Southern California, writes, "Political rights have been circumscribed by race, class and gender since the founding of the United States, when the right to vote was restricted to White men of property.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Those who economically gained the most from slavery were the planter class, owners of large-scale plantations where large numbers of enslaved Africans were held captive and forced to produce crops to create wealth for a White elite.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Although they have gained a greater degree of social equality since the civil rights movement, African Americans have remained stagnant economically, which has hindered their ability to break into the middle class and beyond.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As of 2020, the racial wealth gap between Whites and Blacks remains as large as it was in 1968, with the typical net worth of a White household equivalent to that of 11.5 Black households.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Despite this, African Americans have increased employment rates and gained representation in the highest levels of American government in the post–civil rights era.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] However, widespread racism remains an issue that continues to undermine the development of social status.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Economically, of all the racially Black ethnic groups on the globe, African Americans are the wealthiest and most successful, with one in every fifty African American families being millionaires.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This equates in 2023 to approximately 1.79 million African American millionaires in the United States, which is more than the number of millionaires in any racially Black country, and many other countries, around the world.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In the US, which has the largest per-capita prison population in the world, African Americans are overrepresented as the second-largest population of prison inmates (38%) in 2023, coming second to Whites, who made up 57% of the prison population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to the National Registry of Exonerations, Blacks are roughly 7.5 times more likely to be wrongfully convicted of murder in the US than Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 2012, the New York City Police Department detained people more than 500,000 times under the city's stop-and-frisk law.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Of the total detained, 55% were African-Americans, while Black people made up 20% of the city's population.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American males are more likely to be killed by police when compared to other races.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This is one of the factors that led to the creation of the Black Lives Matter movement in 2013.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to *The Guardian*, "The specter of Karen persisted as Black Lives Matter protests and civil unrest spread around the country following Floyd's murder and reckonings with racism began to roil institutions, toppling careers as well as statues".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In the aftermath of the peak Black Lives Matter protests and widespread police reform efforts in the early 2020s, crime rates surged across the nation, especially in predominantly Black neighborhoods.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Many cities experienced near-record or record levels of violence and other criminal activity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As a result, numerous municipalities scaled back police reform initiatives and increased funding for law enforcement.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] After over 50 years, marriage rates for all Americans began to decline while divorce rates and out-of-wedlock births have climbed.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] These changes have been greatest among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] After more than 70 years of racial parity Black marriage rates began to fall behind Whites.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Single-parent households have become most common, and according to US census figures released in January 2010, only 38% of Black children lived with both their parents.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 2021, statistics show that over 80% marriages in the African American ethnic group marry within their ethnic group.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Black children are overrepresented in the U.S. foster care system.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 2017, Black American children made up 14% of the children population but 22% of those in the foster care system.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Black American children are more than twice as likely to be placed in foster care than White American children.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The first ever anti-miscegenation law was passed by the Maryland General Assembly in 1691, criminalizing interracial marriage.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In a speech in Charleston, Illinois in 1858, Abraham Lincoln stated, "I am not, nor ever have been in favor of making voters or jurors of negroes, nor of qualifying them to hold office, nor to intermarry with white people".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By the late 1800s, 38 US states had anti-miscegenation statutes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By 1924, the ban on interracial marriage was still in force in 29 states.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] While interracial marriage had been legal in California since 1948, in 1957 actor Sammy Davis Jr. faced a backlash for his involvement with White actress Kim Novak.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Harry Cohn, the president of Columbia Pictures, with whom Novak was under contract, gave in to his concerns that a racist backlash against the relationship could hurt the studio.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Davis briefly married Black dancer Loray White in 1958 to protect himself from mob violence.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Inebriated at the wedding ceremony, Davis despairingly said to his best friend, Arthur Silber Jr., "Why won't they let me live my life?" The couple never lived together, and commenced divorce proceedings in September 1958.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 1967 the law was ruled unconstitutional (via the 14th Amendment adopted in 1868) by the US Supreme Court in *Loving v.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 2008, Democrats overwhelmingly voted 70% against California Proposition 8, African Americans voted 58% in favor of it while 42% voted against Proposition 8.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] On May 9, 2012, Barack Obama, the first Black president, became the first US president to support same-sex marriage.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Since Obama's endorsement there has been a rapid growth in support for same-sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As of 2012, 59% of African Americans support same-sex marriage, which is higher than support among the national average (53%) and White Americans (50%).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Polls in North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Missouri, Maryland, Ohio, Florida, and Nevada have also shown an increase in support for same sex marriage among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] On November 6, 2012, Maryland, Maine, and Washington all voted for approve of same-sex marriage, along with Minnesota rejecting a constitutional amendment banning same-sex marriage.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Exit polls in Maryland show about 50% of African Americans voted for same-sex marriage, showing a vast evolution among African Americans on the issue and was crucial in helping pass same-sex marriage in Maryland.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Black Americans hold far more conservative opinions on abortion, extramarital sex, and raising children out of wedlock than Democrats as a whole.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] On financial issues, however, African Americans are in line with Democrats, generally supporting a more progressive tax structure to provide more government spending on social services.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African Americans have fought in every war in the history of the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The gains made by African Americans in the civil rights movement and in the Black Power movement not only obtained certain rights for African Americans but changed American society in far-reaching and fundamentally important ways.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Prior to the 1950s, Black Americans in the South were subject to de jure discrimination, or Jim Crow laws.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] They were often the victims of extreme cruelty and violence, sometimes resulting in deaths: by the post World War II era, African Americans became increasingly discontented with their long-standing inequality.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The civil rights movement marked an enormous change in American social, political, economic and civic life.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Over time, it has changed in fundamental ways the manner in which Blacks and Whites interact with and relate to one another.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Some activists and academics contend that American news media coverage of African American news, concerns, or dilemmas is inadequate, or that the news media present distorted images of African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Johnson founded Black Entertainment Television (BET), a network that targets young African Americans and urban audiences in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Over the years, the network has aired such programming as rap and R&B music videos, urban-oriented movies and television series, and some public affairs programs.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] On Sunday mornings, BET would broadcast Christian programming; the network would also broadcast non-affiliated Christian programs during the early morning hours daily.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] According to Viacom, BET is now a global network that reaches households in the United States, Caribbean, Canada, and the United Kingdom.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The network has gone on to spawn several spin-off channels, including BET Her (originally launched as *BET on Jazz*).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Another network targeting African Americans is TV One.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] TV One is owned by Urban One, founded and controlled by Catherine Hughes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Urban One is one of the nation's largest radio broadcasting companies and the largest African American-owned radio broadcasting company in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In June 2009, NBC News launched a new website named TheGrio.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] It is the first African American video news site that focuses on underrepresented stories in existing national news.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] From their earliest presence in North America, African Americans have significantly contributed literature, art, agricultural skills, cuisine, clothing styles, music, language, and social and technological innovation to American culture.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The cultivation and use of many agricultural products in the United States, such as yams, peanuts, rice, okra, sorghum, grits, watermelon, indigo dyes, and cotton, can be traced to West African and African American influences.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Notable examples include George Washington Carver, who created nearly 500 products from peanuts, sweet potatoes, and pecans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Soul food is a variety of cuisine popular among African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] It is closely related to the cuisine of the Southern United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The descriptive terminology may have originated in the mid-1960s, when *soul* was a common definer used to describe African American culture (for example, soul music).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African Americans were the first peoples in the United States to make fried chicken, along with Scottish immigrants to the South.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Although the Scottish had been frying chicken before they emigrated, they lacked the spices and flavor that African Americans had used when preparing the meal.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The Scottish American settlers therefore adopted the African American method of seasoning chicken.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] However, fried chicken was generally a rare meal in the African American community and was usually reserved for special events or celebrations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African-American English is a variety (dialect, ethnolect, and sociolect) of American English, commonly spoken by urban working-class and largely bi-dialectal middle-class African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] It shares parts of its grammar and phonology with the Southern American English dialect.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American English differs from Standard American English (SAE) in certain pronunciation characteristics, tense usage, and grammatical structures, which were derived from West African languages (particularly those belonging to the Niger–Congo family).
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Virtually all habitual speakers of African American English can understand and communicate in Standard American English.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As with all linguistic forms, AAVE's usage is influenced by various factors, including geographical, educational and socioeconomic background, as well as formality of setting.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Additionally, there are many literary uses of this variety of English, particularly in African American literature.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Other languages are spoken by specific sub-communities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The Gullah language is an English-based creole language spoken mostly in the coastal regions of South Carolina and Georgia by the Gullah; an off-shoot of this is Afro-Seminole Creole spoken by Black Seminoles mostly now in Mexico and Brackettville, Texas.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Louisiana Creole is a French-based creole and spoken mostly in Louisiana.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African-American names are part of the cultural traditions of African Americans, most of these cultural names having no connection to Africa but strictly an African American cultural practice that developed in the United States during enslavement.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This new evidence became apparent by census records which show African Americans and White Americans, though they spoke the same language, chose to use different names even during times of enslavement, which is where and when the development of African American cultural names began.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Prior to this newer information, it was only thought that before the 1950s, and 1960s, most African-American names closely resembled those used within European-American culture.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Babies of that era were generally given a few common names, with children using nicknames to distinguish the various people with the same name.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] With the rise of 1960s civil rights movement, there was a dramatic increase in names of various origins.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By the 1970s, and 1980s, it had become common among African Americans to invent new names for themselves, although many of these invented names took elements from popular existing names.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Prefixes such as La/Le, Da/De, Ra/Re and Ja/Je, and suffixes like -ique/iqua, -isha and -aun/-awn are common, as are inventive spellings for common names.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The book *Baby Names Now: From Classic to Cool—The Very Last Word on First Names* places the origins of "La" names in African-American culture in New Orleans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Even with the rise of inventive names, it is still common for African Americans to use biblical, historical, or traditional European names.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Daniel, Christopher, Michael, David, James, Joseph, and Matthew were thus among the most frequent names for African-American boys in 2013.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The name LaKeisha is typically considered American in origin but has elements that were drawn from both French and West/Central African roots.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Names such as LaTanisha, JaMarcus, DeAndre, and Shaniqua were created in the same way.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Punctuation marks are seen more often within African American names than other American names, such as the names Mo'nique and D'Andre.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American music is one of the most pervasive African American cultural influences in the United States today and is among the most dominant in mainstream popular music.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Hip-hop, R&B, funk, rock and roll, soul, blues, and other contemporary American musical forms originated in Black communities and evolved from other Black forms of music, including blues, doo-wop, barbershop, ragtime, bluegrass, jazz, and gospel music.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American-derived musical forms have also influenced and been incorporated into virtually every other popular music genre in the world, including country and techno.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African Americans have also had an important role in American dance.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Jones, a prominent modern choreographer and dancer, has included historical African American themes in his work, particularly in the piece "Last Supper at Uncle Tom's Cabin/The Promised Land".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Likewise, Alvin Ailey's artistic work, including his "Revelations" based on his experience growing up as an African American in the South during the 1930s, has had a significant influence on modern dance.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Another form of dance, stepping, is an African American tradition whose performance and competition has been formalized through the traditionally Black fraternities and sororities at universities.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Discussions of race and sports in the United States, where the two subjects have always been intertwined in American history, have focused to a great extent on African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Depending on the type of sport and performance level, African Americans are reported to be over- or under-represented.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African Americans compose the highest percentage of the minority groups active at the professional level, but are among those who show the lowest participation overall.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] And though the list of African Americans in professional sports remains high, it only represents a small fraction of aspiring black athletes.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Many African American authors have written stories, poems, and essays influenced by their experiences as African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American literature is a major genre in American literature.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Famous examples include Langston Hughes, James Baldwin, Richard Wright, Zora Neale Hurston, Ralph Ellison, Nobel Prize winner Toni Morrison, and Maya Angelou.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African American inventors have created many widely used devices in the world and have contributed to international innovation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Norbert Rillieux created the technique for converting sugar cane juice into white sugar crystals.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Moreover, Rillieux left Louisiana in 1854 and went to France, where he spent ten years working with the Champollions deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphics from the Rosetta Stone.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Most slave inventors were nameless, such as the slave owned by the Confederate President Jefferson Davis who designed the ship propeller used by the Confederate navy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By 1913, over 1,000 inventions were patented by Black Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Among the most notable inventors were Jan Matzeliger, who developed the first machine to mass-produce shoes, and Elijah McCoy, who invented automatic lubrication devices for steam engines.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Granville Woods had 35 patents to improve electric railway systems, including the first system to allow moving trains to communicate.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Morgan developed the first automatic traffic signal and gas mask.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Lewis Howard Latimer invented an improvement for the incandescent light bulb.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] More recent inventors include Frederick McKinley Jones, who invented the movable refrigeration unit for food transport in trucks and trains.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Lloyd Quarterman worked with six other Black scientists on the creation of the atomic bomb (code named the Manhattan Project) and helped develop the first nuclear reactor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] As part of the preservation of their culture, African Americans have continuously launched their own publications and publishing houses, such as Robert Sengstacke Abbott, founder of the Chicago Defender newspaper, and Carter G.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Woodson, the founder of Black History Month who spent over thirty years documenting and publishing African American history in journals and books.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The Johnson Publishing Company, founded by John H.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Johnson in 1942, is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* was popularized by Jesse Jackson in the 1980s, although there are recorded uses from the 18th and 19th centuries, for example, in post-emancipation holidays and conferences.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Earlier terms also used to describe Americans of African ancestry referred more to skin color than to ancestry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Other terms (such as *colored*, *person of color*, or *negro*) were included in the wording of various laws and legal decisions which some thought were being used as tools of White supremacy and oppression.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] A 16-page pamphlet entitled "A Sermon on the Capture of Lord Cornwallis" is notable for the attribution of its authorship to "An *African American*".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Published in 1782, the book's use of this phrase predates any other yet identified by more than 50 years.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In the 1980s, the term *African American* was advanced to give descendants of American slaves, and other American Blacks who lived through the slavery era, a heritage and a cultural base.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term was popularized in Black communities around the country via word of mouth and ultimately received mainstream use after Jesse Jackson's use in 1988.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Subsequently, major media outlets adopted it.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Surveys in the 1990s and the first decade of the 21st century showed that the majority of Black Americans had no preference for *African American* versus *Black American*, although they had a slight preference for the latter in personal settings and the former in more formal settings.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By 2021, according to polling from Gallup, 58% of Black Americans expressed no preference for what their group should be called, with 17% each preferring *Black* and *African-American*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In 2023, the government released a new more detailed breakdown due to the rise in racially Black immigration into the US, listing African American as a compound termed ethnicity, distinguished from other racially Black ethnicities such as Nigerian, Jamaican etc.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term *African American* embraces pan-Africanism as earlier enunciated by prominent African thinkers such as Marcus Garvey, W.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term *Afro-Usonian*, and variations of such, are more rarely used.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] In preparation for the 2010 US census, a marketing and outreach plan called *2010 Census Integrated Communications Campaign Plan* (ICC) recognized and defined African Americans as Black people born in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] From the ICC perspective, African Americans are one of three groups of Black people in the United States: African Americans, Black Africans, and Afro-Caribbeans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The ICC plan was to reach the three groups by acknowledging that each group has its own sense of community that is based on geography and ethnicity.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The best way to market the census process toward any of the three groups is to reach them through their own unique communication channels and not treat the entire Black population of the US as though they are all African Americans with a single ethnic and geographical background.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Historically, "race mixing" between Black and White people was taboo in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] So-called anti-miscegenation laws, barring Blacks and Whites from marrying or having sex, were established in colonial America as early as 1691, and endured in many Southern states until the Supreme Court ruled them unconstitutional in *Loving v.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The taboo among American Whites surrounding White-Black relations is a historical consequence of the oppression and racial segregation of African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Harvard University historian Henry Louis Gates Jr. wrote in 2009 that "African Americans...are a racially mixed or mulatto people—deeply and overwhelmingly so".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] After the Emancipation Proclamation, Chinese American men married African American women in high proportions to their total marriage numbers due to few Chinese American women being in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] African slaves and their descendants have also had a history of cultural exchange and intermarriage with Native Americans, although they did not necessarily retain social, cultural or linguistic ties to Native peoples.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] There are also increasing intermarriages and offspring between non-Hispanic Blacks and Hispanics of any race, especially between Puerto Ricans and African Americans.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Racially mixed marriages have become increasingly accepted in the United States since the civil rights movement.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] A Gallup poll conducted in 2013 found that 84% of Whites and 96% of Blacks approved of interracial marriage, and 87% overall.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Black men are more than twice as likely to date and marry interracially than Black women.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] At the end of World War II, some African American military men stationed in Asia and Europe impregnated local non-Black women, resulting in the birth of thousands of mixed-race children called "Brown Babies".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Some of these families later immigrated to the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] However, some mixed-race children, especially in Japan, were placed in orphanages due to social stigmas associated with half-Black fatherless children in the 1950s.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Author Debra Dickerson has argued that the term *Black* should refer strictly to the descendants of Africans who were brought to America as slaves, and not to the sons and daughters of Black immigrants who lack that ancestry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Thus, under her definition, President Barack Obama, who is the son of a Kenyan, is not Black.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] "Lumping us all together", Dickerson wrote, "erases the significance of slavery and continuing racism while giving the appearance of progress." Similar comments have been made concerning Kamala Harris, the daughter of a Jamaican immigrant, who was elected vice president in 2020.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The American Descendants of Slavery (ADOS) movement coalesces around this view, arguing that Black descendants of American slavery deserve a separate ethnic category that distinguishes them from other Black groups in the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Their terminology has gained popularity in some circles, but others have criticized the movement for a perceived bias against (especially poor and Black) immigrants, and for its often inflammatory rhetoric.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Politicians such as Obama and Harris have received especially pointed criticism from the movement, as neither are ADOS and have spoken out at times against policies specific to them.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Most notably, Malcolm X and Kwame Ture expressed similar views that African Americans are Africans who "happen to be in America", and should not claim or identify as being American if they are fighting for Black (New Afrikan) liberation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Historically, this is due to the enslavement of Africans during the transatlantic slave trade, ongoing anti-Black violence, and structural racism in countries like the United States.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Before the independence of the Thirteen Colonies until the abolition of slavery in 1865, an African American slave was commonly known as a *negro*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] *Free negro* was the legal status in the territory of an African American person who was not enslaved.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term was used until the second quarter of the 20th century, when it was considered outmoded – although it was retained in the name of the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) – and generally gave way again to the exclusive use of *negro*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By the 1940s, the term was commonly capitalized (*Negro*); but by the mid-1960s, it was considered disparaging.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] By the end of the 20th century, *negro* had come to be considered inappropriate and was rarely used and perceived as a pejorative.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term is rarely used by younger Black people, but remained in use by many older African Americans who had grown up with the term, particularly in the Southern US.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The term remains in use in some contexts, such as the United Negro College Fund, an American philanthropic organization.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] There are many other deliberately insulting terms, many of which were in common use (e.g., *nigger*), but had become unacceptable in normal discourse before the end of the 20th century.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] One exception is the use, among the Black community, of the slur *nigger* rendered as *nigga*, representing the pronunciation of the word in African American English.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] This usage has been popularized by American rap and hip-hop music cultures and is used as part of an in-group lexicon and speech.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] It is not necessarily derogatory and, when used among Black people, the word is often used to mean "homie" or "friend".
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] Acceptance of intra-group usage of the word *nigga* is still debated, although it has established a foothold among younger generations.
[src:charles-william-eliot/african-americans-p03] The NAACP denounces the use of both *nigga* and *nigger*.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot was born a scion of the wealthy Eliot family of Boston.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He was the son of politician Samuel Atkins Eliot and his wife Mary (née Lyman), and was the grandchild of banker Samuel Eliot and merchant Theodore Lyman of the Lyman Estate.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] His grandfather was one of the wealthiest merchants of Boston.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He was one of five siblings and the only boy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot graduated from Boston Latin School in 1849 and from Harvard University in 1853.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He was later made an honorary member of the Hasty Pudding.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Although he had high expectations and obvious scientific talents, the first fifteen years of Eliot's career were less than auspicious.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He was appointed Tutor in Mathematics at Harvard in the fall of 1854, and studied chemistry with Josiah P.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] In 1858, he was promoted to Assistant Professor of Mathematics and Chemistry.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He taught competently, wrote some technical pieces on chemical impurities in industrial metals, and busied himself with schemes for the reform of Harvard's Lawrence Scientific School.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] But his real goal, appointment to the Rumford Professorship of Chemistry, eluded him.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] This was a particularly bitter blow because of a change in his family's economic circumstances—the financial failure of his father, Samuel Atkins Eliot, in the Panic of 1857.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot had to face the fact that "he had nothing to look to but his teacher's salary and a legacy left to him by his grandfather Lyman." After a bitter struggle over the Rumford chair, Eliot left Harvard in 1863.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] His friends assumed that he would "be obliged to cut chemistry and go into business in order to earn a livelihood for his family." But instead, he used his grandfather's large legacy and a small borrowed sum to spend the next two years studying the educational systems of the Old World in Europe.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot's approach to investigating European education was unusual.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He did not confine his attention to educational institutions, but explored the role of education in every aspect of national life.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] When Eliot visited schools, he took an interest in every aspect of institutional operation, from curriculum and methods of instruction through physical arrangements and custodial services.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot understood the interdependence of education and enterprise.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Lyman, he discussed the value to the German chemical industry of discoveries made in university laboratories.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He also recognized that, while European universities depended on government for support, American institutions would have to draw on the resources of the wealthy.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] While Eliot was in Europe, he was again presented with the opportunity to enter the world of active business.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] The Merrimack Mills, one of the largest textile mills in the United States, tendered him an invitation to become its superintendent.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] In spite of the urgings of his friends and the attractiveness of what for the time was the enormous salary of $5000 (plus a good house, rent free), Eliot, after giving considerable thought to the offer, turned it down.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] One of his biographers speculated that he surely realized by this time that he had a strong taste for organizing and administration.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] During nearly two years in Europe he had found himself as much fascinated by what he could learn concerning the methods by which science could be made to help industry as by what he discovered about the organization of institutions of learning.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] He was thinking much about what his own young country needed, and his hopes for the United States took account of industry and commerce as well as the field of academic endeavor.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] To be the chief executive officer of a particular business offered only a limited range of influence; but to stand at the intersection of the realm of production and the realm of knowledge offered considerably more.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] In the 1800s, American colleges, controlled by clergymen, continued to embrace classical curricula that had little relevance to an industrializing nation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Few offered courses in the sciences, modern languages, history, or political economy — and only a handful had graduate or professional schools.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] As businessmen became increasingly reluctant to send their sons to schools whose curricula offered nothing useful — or to donate money for their support, some educational leaders began exploring ways of making higher education more attractive.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Some backed the establishment of specialized schools of science and technology, like Harvard's Lawrence Scientific School, Yale's Sheffield Scientific School, and the newly chartered Massachusetts Institute of Technology, about to offer its first classes in 1865.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Others proposed abandoning the classical curriculum, in favor of more vocational offerings.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Harvard was in the middle of this crisis.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] After three undistinguished short-term clerical Harvard presidencies in a ten-year period, Boston's business leaders, many of them Harvard alumni, were pressing for change — though with no clear idea of the kinds of changes they wanted.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] On his return to the United States in 1865, Eliot accepted an appointment as Professor of Analytical Chemistry at the newly founded Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] In that year, an important revolution occurred in the government of Harvard University.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] An opinion had long been gaining ground that it would be better for the community and the interests of learning, as well as for the university, if the power to elect the overseers were transferred from the legislature to the graduates of the college.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] This change was made in 1865, and at the same time the governor and other state officers ceased to form part of the board.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] The effect of this change was to greatly strengthen the interest of the alumni in the management of the university, and thus to prepare the way for extensive and thorough reforms.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Thomas Hill resigned the presidency, and after a considerable interregnum Eliot succeeded to that office in 1869.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Early in 1869, Eliot had presented his ideas about reforming American higher education in a compelling two-part article, "The New Education," in *The Atlantic Monthly*, the nation's leading journal of opinion.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] "We are fighting a wilderness, physical and moral," Eliot declared in setting forth his vision of the American university, "for this fight we must be trained and armed." The articles resonated powerfully with the businessmen who controlled the Harvard Corporation.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Shortly after their appearance, merely 35 years old, he was elected as the youngest president in the history of the nation's oldest university.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] Eliot's educational vision incorporated important elements of Unitarian and Emersonian ideas about character development, framed by a pragmatic understanding of the role of higher education in economic and political leadership.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] His concern in "The New Education" was not merely curriculum, but the ultimate utility of education.
[src:charles-william-eliot/charles-william-eliot] A college education could enable a student to make intelligent choices, but should not attempt to provide specialized vocational or technical training.
